WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.460 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:02.460 --> 00:00:18.767 align:middle line:90%


00:00:18.767 --> 00:00:20.850 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA MEREDITH: It
appears Western civilization

00:00:20.850 --> 00:00:23.800 align:middle line:84%
has been operating under a
fallacy at a deeply fundamental

00:00:23.800 --> 00:00:26.420 align:middle line:84%
level-- the notion of
survival of the fittest,

00:00:26.420 --> 00:00:28.477 align:middle line:90%
or survival through competition.

00:00:28.477 --> 00:00:30.810 align:middle line:84%
You don't need to look far
to see where this mindset has

00:00:30.810 --> 00:00:32.509 align:middle line:84%
taken us, beginning
with Wall Street

00:00:32.509 --> 00:00:33.840 align:middle line:90%
and the world of politics.

00:00:33.840 --> 00:00:36.800 align:middle line:84%
But this is equally damaging
on the most personal levels.

00:00:36.800 --> 00:00:39.650 align:middle line:84%
According to Lynne McTaggart,
author of "The Bond."

00:00:39.650 --> 00:00:40.740 align:middle line:90%
And Lynne joins us today.

00:00:40.740 --> 00:00:43.100 align:middle line:84%
And first of all, before we
go anywhere else with this,

00:00:43.100 --> 00:00:45.830 align:middle line:84%
I have to say, this
is a must read.

00:00:45.830 --> 00:00:47.170 align:middle line:90%
This is really a must read.

00:00:47.170 --> 00:00:49.980 align:middle line:84%
If you're look-- it's how to
fix your following down world.

00:00:49.980 --> 00:00:52.860 align:middle line:84%
I think everyone of us can
relate to that subtitle.

00:00:52.860 --> 00:00:56.050 align:middle line:84%
And part of the
attraction to this for me

00:00:56.050 --> 00:00:59.246 align:middle line:84%
is that you're steeping
it, as always, in science.

00:00:59.246 --> 00:01:01.620 align:middle line:84%
And last time I sat with you,
we were doing the interview

00:01:01.620 --> 00:01:04.120 align:middle line:90%
on "The Intention Experiments."

00:01:04.120 --> 00:01:07.620 align:middle line:84%
And now we're going into--
we're segue waying into this.

00:01:07.620 --> 00:01:10.934 align:middle line:84%
But before we even go there,
Lynne, I would like to--

00:01:10.934 --> 00:01:11.850 align:middle line:90%
and you're everywhere.

00:01:11.850 --> 00:01:13.590 align:middle line:90%
This came in my mail.

00:01:13.590 --> 00:01:14.634 align:middle line:90%
You're everywhere.

00:01:14.634 --> 00:01:16.300 align:middle line:84%
You did a couple
interviews this morning

00:01:16.300 --> 00:01:18.180 align:middle line:84%
after coming in from
London last night.

00:01:18.180 --> 00:01:19.990 align:middle line:84%
But let's talk about
"The Fountainhead"

00:01:19.990 --> 00:01:21.740 align:middle line:84%
before we get into the
rest of this story.

00:01:21.740 --> 00:01:24.835 align:middle line:84%
Because that's really
a fascinating glimpse.

00:01:24.835 --> 00:01:27.210 align:middle line:84%
Why don't you do the background
to it, and why you put it

00:01:27.210 --> 00:01:28.790 align:middle line:90%
in this particular chapter.

00:01:28.790 --> 00:01:31.290 align:middle line:84%
>>LYNNE MCTAGGART: Well, we
in America, we in the west,

00:01:31.290 --> 00:01:33.850 align:middle line:84%
really revere our
lone wolf heroes.

00:01:33.850 --> 00:01:37.610 align:middle line:84%
You know, whether they come
in the guise of Nicolas Cage,

00:01:37.610 --> 00:01:40.540 align:middle line:84%
or Humphrey Bogart,
or even Superman,

00:01:40.540 --> 00:01:42.870 align:middle line:84%
the whole idea of the
individual with his fist up

00:01:42.870 --> 00:01:44.470 align:middle line:90%
against the establishment.

00:01:44.470 --> 00:01:46.480 align:middle line:84%
And I thought the
real epitome of this

00:01:46.480 --> 00:01:49.940 align:middle line:84%
was Howard Roark in the
movie, "The Fountainhead,"

00:01:49.940 --> 00:01:52.290 align:middle line:84%
or the-- which came from the
book, "The Fountainhead,"

00:01:52.290 --> 00:01:53.540 align:middle line:90%
by Ayn Rand.

00:01:53.540 --> 00:01:56.840 align:middle line:84%
And in that, Gary
Cooper is Howard Roark.

00:01:56.840 --> 00:02:00.380 align:middle line:84%
And he's the
uncompromising architect

00:02:00.380 --> 00:02:03.400 align:middle line:84%
who decides he wants to
build buildings his way.

00:02:03.400 --> 00:02:05.940 align:middle line:84%
So he builds-- he
designs a building that's

00:02:05.940 --> 00:02:08.199 align:middle line:84%
supposed to be a
public housing project.

00:02:08.199 --> 00:02:10.750 align:middle line:84%
And the people who
commissioned him change it.

00:02:10.750 --> 00:02:12.020 align:middle line:90%
They bastardize it.

00:02:12.020 --> 00:02:15.290 align:middle line:84%
And he's so incensed by
this that he blows it up.

00:02:15.290 --> 00:02:18.440 align:middle line:84%
And so he, of course,
is brought to trial

00:02:18.440 --> 00:02:22.340 align:middle line:84%
because he's destroyed
public property.

00:02:22.340 --> 00:02:24.800 align:middle line:84%
And he chooses to
defend himself.

00:02:24.800 --> 00:02:26.770 align:middle line:84%
And that gives Ayn
Rand the chance

00:02:26.770 --> 00:02:31.490 align:middle line:84%
to give him the mouthpiece
for her philosophy, which

00:02:31.490 --> 00:02:33.914 align:middle line:84%
is essentially an every
man for himself philosophy.

00:02:33.914 --> 00:02:34.580 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: It is.

00:02:34.580 --> 00:02:35.700 align:middle line:90%
And can I read that part?

00:02:35.700 --> 00:02:36.700 align:middle line:90%
>>MCTAGGART: Definitely.

00:02:36.700 --> 00:02:38.260 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: It's a quote from him.

00:02:38.260 --> 00:02:40.800 align:middle line:84%
It says, "The creator
who lives for his work

00:02:40.800 --> 00:02:43.050 align:middle line:90%
needs to no other men.

00:02:43.050 --> 00:02:44.840 align:middle line:84%
Wheeling around,
he faces the jury.

00:02:44.840 --> 00:02:48.260 align:middle line:84%
I do not recognize anyone's
right to one minute of my life,

00:02:48.260 --> 00:02:50.300 align:middle line:84%
nor any part of my
energy, no matter

00:02:50.300 --> 00:02:52.550 align:middle line:84%
who makes the claim,
how large their number,

00:02:52.550 --> 00:02:54.300 align:middle line:90%
or how great their need.

00:02:54.300 --> 00:02:56.430 align:middle line:84%
The integrity of a
man's creative work

00:02:56.430 --> 00:02:59.689 align:middle line:84%
is of greater importance than
any charitable endeavor."

00:02:59.689 --> 00:03:00.980 align:middle line:90%
That's a very strong statement.

00:03:00.980 --> 00:03:04.960 align:middle line:84%
And I have to say, when I saw
the movie, it's like yes, yes.

00:03:04.960 --> 00:03:08.290 align:middle line:84%
I mean, we all when we see this
and the way it was portrayed

00:03:08.290 --> 00:03:11.510 align:middle line:84%
and the way we've
been raised societally

00:03:11.510 --> 00:03:14.400 align:middle line:84%
and individually,
you think, yes.

00:03:14.400 --> 00:03:17.240 align:middle line:84%
One has to stand up for
one's artistic expression.

00:03:17.240 --> 00:03:20.455 align:middle line:84%
It can't be wiped out by
something more mundane.

00:03:20.455 --> 00:03:23.860 align:middle line:84%
But this is actually
dangerous thinking

00:03:23.860 --> 00:03:25.130 align:middle line:90%
from where you're sitting.

00:03:25.130 --> 00:03:27.310 align:middle line:84%
>>MCTAGGART: It's toxic
thinking, that I mean,

00:03:27.310 --> 00:03:30.470 align:middle line:84%
here's what happens in
the book and in the movie.

00:03:30.470 --> 00:03:35.070 align:middle line:84%
He gets acquitted despite
having blown up a city block.

00:03:35.070 --> 00:03:36.780 align:middle line:90%
He gets the girl.

00:03:36.780 --> 00:03:38.740 align:middle line:84%
He gets to build the
building his way.

00:03:38.740 --> 00:03:41.300 align:middle line:84%
And at the very end,
he's standing there

00:03:41.300 --> 00:03:43.060 align:middle line:90%
like the super colossus.

00:03:43.060 --> 00:03:46.080 align:middle line:84%
He's like the
Nietzschean Superman.

00:03:46.080 --> 00:03:49.580 align:middle line:84%
But my real point is he's the
perfect candidate for a heart

00:03:49.580 --> 00:03:50.190 align:middle line:90%
attack.

00:03:50.190 --> 00:03:51.550 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:03:51.550 --> 00:03:52.264 align:middle line:90%
Exactly.

00:03:52.264 --> 00:03:54.680 align:middle line:84%
And we are-- I just wanted to
use that as an illustration.

00:03:54.680 --> 00:03:56.620 align:middle line:84%
Because many people
have read the book,

00:03:56.620 --> 00:03:58.720 align:middle line:84%
or they have seen the
movie with Gary Cooper.

00:03:58.720 --> 00:04:01.170 align:middle line:84%
And it is a very
rousing, emotional moment

00:04:01.170 --> 00:04:02.340 align:middle line:90%
when he makes this speech.

00:04:02.340 --> 00:04:04.820 align:middle line:84%
And most people in the
west I think probably do

00:04:04.820 --> 00:04:07.010 align:middle line:84%
relate to it on an
emotional level.

00:04:07.010 --> 00:04:08.910 align:middle line:90%
And it's unconscious.

00:04:08.910 --> 00:04:10.290 align:middle line:90%
It's unconscious.

00:04:10.290 --> 00:04:13.580 align:middle line:84%
And yet, as we're going
to see when we go further

00:04:13.580 --> 00:04:19.450 align:middle line:84%
into this work here, that really
has-- that part of our thinking

00:04:19.450 --> 00:04:24.200 align:middle line:84%
has to die away to another
type of individuality

00:04:24.200 --> 00:04:25.501 align:middle line:90%
within a collective.

00:04:25.501 --> 00:04:26.750 align:middle line:90%
But first let's talk about it.

00:04:26.750 --> 00:04:28.666 align:middle line:84%
How did you go from "The
Intention Experiment"

00:04:28.666 --> 00:04:30.060 align:middle line:90%
into "The Bond?"

00:04:30.060 --> 00:04:32.320 align:middle line:84%
>>MCTAGGART: Well, there
were some big reasons

00:04:32.320 --> 00:04:35.200 align:middle line:84%
for doing this book, and
there were some small reasons.

00:04:35.200 --> 00:04:37.380 align:middle line:84%
First of all, I've
always felt from the time

00:04:37.380 --> 00:04:40.300 align:middle line:84%
I'd written "The Field" that
I had to write a book that

00:04:40.300 --> 00:04:43.355 align:middle line:84%
basically said, how do we
live what I'd discovered.

00:04:43.355 --> 00:04:46.990 align:middle line:84%
You know, I discovered that we
were all part of this larger

00:04:46.990 --> 00:04:49.620 align:middle line:90%
field, this larger energy field.

00:04:49.620 --> 00:04:54.000 align:middle line:84%
So I thought well, that
really contradicts everything

00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:57.760 align:middle line:84%
we think about who we are and
how we're supposed to live.

00:04:57.760 --> 00:05:01.460 align:middle line:84%
I also felt I needed to write
a bigger part of the story.

00:05:01.460 --> 00:05:05.320 align:middle line:84%
Because many things write
the story we live by.

00:05:05.320 --> 00:05:07.140 align:middle line:84%
But science is
really the thing that

00:05:07.140 --> 00:05:08.840 align:middle line:90%
writes the biggest chapter.

00:05:08.840 --> 00:05:09.520 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:05:09.520 --> 00:05:11.603 align:middle line:84%
>>MCTAGGART: You know,
science defines who we are.

00:05:11.603 --> 00:05:14.710 align:middle line:84%
And from there, we determine
how we're supposed to live.

00:05:14.710 --> 00:05:17.530 align:middle line:84%
And the scientific
story thus far

00:05:17.530 --> 00:05:21.330 align:middle line:84%
has been a story of
individualism-- extreme

00:05:21.330 --> 00:05:22.300 align:middle line:90%
individualism.

00:05:22.300 --> 00:05:25.800 align:middle line:84%
You know, that life is full of
individual, very well behaved

00:05:25.800 --> 00:05:26.310 align:middle line:90%
things.

00:05:26.310 --> 00:05:27.810 align:middle line:90%
That's what Newton told us.

00:05:27.810 --> 00:05:30.140 align:middle line:84%
And then Darwin told
us that those things

00:05:30.140 --> 00:05:32.180 align:middle line:84%
are in competition
with each other.

00:05:32.180 --> 00:05:36.390 align:middle line:84%
And so from there, we've sort
of defined life as a race

00:05:36.390 --> 00:05:37.880 align:middle line:90%
to the finish line.

00:05:37.880 --> 00:05:40.440 align:middle line:84%
And that has pretty much
influenced everything

00:05:40.440 --> 00:05:43.620 align:middle line:84%
we do in our lives,
every structure we have.

00:05:43.620 --> 00:05:47.110 align:middle line:84%
Our educational model
is built on competition.

00:05:47.110 --> 00:05:50.720 align:middle line:84%
Our business model, our
financial model, competition.

00:05:50.720 --> 00:05:54.270 align:middle line:84%
Our neighborhood
model-- god forbid

00:05:54.270 --> 00:05:56.150 align:middle line:84%
your neighbor gets
a Mercedes when

00:05:56.150 --> 00:05:58.160 align:middle line:90%
you're still driving a Ford.

00:05:58.160 --> 00:06:01.670 align:middle line:84%
Even our relationships are
very competitive these days.

00:06:01.670 --> 00:06:05.680 align:middle line:84%
So the first question I had
was, is this the right story?

00:06:05.680 --> 00:06:08.070 align:middle line:90%
Was it supposed to be like this?

00:06:08.070 --> 00:06:09.790 align:middle line:84%
I also wanted to
try to figure out

00:06:09.790 --> 00:06:12.530 align:middle line:84%
why we're in the mess
we're in right now.

00:06:12.530 --> 00:06:15.460 align:middle line:84%
All we hear everywhere
is it's the end of this.

00:06:15.460 --> 00:06:16.450 align:middle line:90%
It's the end of that.

00:06:16.450 --> 00:06:17.020 align:middle line:90%
It's the end of capitalism.

00:06:17.020 --> 00:06:17.560 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Just
reading the headlines

00:06:17.560 --> 00:06:19.934 align:middle line:84%
this morning. "Wall Street
Journal" and "New York Times."

00:06:19.934 --> 00:06:20.935 align:middle line:90%
It's enough.

00:06:20.935 --> 00:06:21.560 align:middle line:90%
The front page.

00:06:21.560 --> 00:06:22.600 align:middle line:90%
I can't read anymore.

00:06:22.600 --> 00:06:22.830 align:middle line:90%
>>MCTAGGART: No

00:06:22.830 --> 00:06:24.130 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: It's all falling down.

00:06:24.130 --> 00:06:25.610 align:middle line:84%
>>MCTAGGART: It's
all falling down.

00:06:25.610 --> 00:06:28.160 align:middle line:84%
And so our world
is falling down.

00:06:28.160 --> 00:06:30.190 align:middle line:84%
And you know, the
final reason I wrote

00:06:30.190 --> 00:06:32.290 align:middle line:90%
it was a very personal reason.

00:06:32.290 --> 00:06:33.760 align:middle line:90%
I have two daughters.

00:06:33.760 --> 00:06:36.440 align:middle line:84%
And one of my daughters
is a talented actress.

00:06:36.440 --> 00:06:40.990 align:middle line:84%
And she was given the main
role in her school play.

00:06:40.990 --> 00:06:44.000 align:middle line:84%
Suddenly, she was shunted
to a more minor role.

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:45.780 align:middle line:84%
And I could never
find out the reason

00:06:45.780 --> 00:06:51.270 align:middle line:84%
until another girl let slip
that a third girl had lied when

00:06:51.270 --> 00:06:53.060 align:middle line:84%
a new director came
on board in order

00:06:53.060 --> 00:06:55.640 align:middle line:84%
to take over the role
given my daughter.

00:06:55.640 --> 00:06:58.230 align:middle line:90%
And I was appalled by this.

00:06:58.230 --> 00:07:00.280 align:middle line:84%
So I went to talk
to the mom about it.

00:07:00.280 --> 00:07:02.650 align:middle line:90%
And I brought it up tactfully.

00:07:02.650 --> 00:07:04.550 align:middle line:84%
And the mother just sort
of shrugged me aside

00:07:04.550 --> 00:07:07.880 align:middle line:84%
and said well, you
know, that's life.

00:07:07.880 --> 00:07:10.800 align:middle line:84%
And I was appalled by this until
I started thinking about it

00:07:10.800 --> 00:07:12.370 align:middle line:90%
and thought well, yeah.

00:07:12.370 --> 00:07:16.010 align:middle line:84%
This is the life we've
created for ourselves.

00:07:16.010 --> 00:07:19.300 align:middle line:84%
But as I said, is it's
supposed to be like this?

00:07:19.300 --> 00:07:22.410 align:middle line:84%
Is it all supposed to
be I win, you lose?

00:07:22.410 --> 00:07:26.660 align:middle line:84%
And so that got me looking into
not only physics this time,

00:07:26.660 --> 00:07:31.930 align:middle line:84%
but biology, anthropology,
all the "ologies."

00:07:31.930 --> 00:07:35.160 align:middle line:84%
And what I came
up with was no, it

00:07:35.160 --> 00:07:37.280 align:middle line:90%
wasn't supposed to be like this.

00:07:37.280 --> 00:07:39.200 align:middle line:90%
Nature-- Darwin was wrong.

00:07:39.200 --> 00:07:42.040 align:middle line:84%
Nature hasn't designed
us to compete.

00:07:42.040 --> 00:07:46.560 align:middle line:84%
Nature has designed us,
in every way, to connect.

00:07:46.560 --> 00:07:48.530 align:middle line:84%
In fact, nature
has designed us not

00:07:48.530 --> 00:07:50.910 align:middle line:90%
to be individual in any way.

00:07:50.910 --> 00:07:54.040 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And we are,
whether we can understand it

00:07:54.040 --> 00:07:56.100 align:middle line:84%
through the lens that
we've been living through,

00:07:56.100 --> 00:07:57.900 align:middle line:84%
we are all very
deeply connected,

00:07:57.900 --> 00:08:00.710 align:middle line:84%
not just with each other
but with our environment,

00:08:00.710 --> 00:08:03.060 align:middle line:90%
with the cosmos.

00:08:03.060 --> 00:08:07.415 align:middle line:84%
And yet at the same time,
how many thoughts a day

00:08:07.415 --> 00:08:09.130 align:middle line:84%
do any one of us
have that put us

00:08:09.130 --> 00:08:11.170 align:middle line:84%
in direct competition
with somebody

00:08:11.170 --> 00:08:13.220 align:middle line:84%
else down to the
most mundane levels?

00:08:13.220 --> 00:08:17.970 align:middle line:84%
As you say in your book, we're
not really living who we are,

00:08:17.970 --> 00:08:21.620 align:middle line:84%
and that every day is set
up as a battleground for one

00:08:21.620 --> 00:08:25.300 align:middle line:84%
tiny competition after another,
to the point where no wonder

00:08:25.300 --> 00:08:28.200 align:middle line:84%
we have high blood pressure,
obesity, and everything else.

00:08:28.200 --> 00:08:31.990 align:middle line:84%
It is extremely
anxiety-producing

00:08:31.990 --> 00:08:35.309 align:middle line:84%
to put ourselves in this
mode of competition.

00:08:35.309 --> 00:08:37.766 align:middle line:84%
Talk about it on some of the
mundane levels we go through.

00:08:37.766 --> 00:08:39.390 align:middle line:84%
I love the way you
did it in your book.

00:08:39.390 --> 00:08:43.129 align:middle line:84%
Day in and day out, the ways in
which we're ready to do battle.

00:08:43.129 --> 00:08:45.670 align:middle line:84%
>>MCTAGGART: Well, you know, we
have a metaphor of ourselves,

00:08:45.670 --> 00:08:49.240 align:middle line:84%
or an image of ourselves as
the hero up against it all.

00:08:49.240 --> 00:08:51.330 align:middle line:90%
I mean, that's the way we do it.

00:08:51.330 --> 00:08:55.920 align:middle line:84%
And when you think about it,
we worry about everything

00:08:55.920 --> 00:08:57.970 align:middle line:84%
from the guy who's
going to usurp us

00:08:57.970 --> 00:09:02.020 align:middle line:84%
at our job, the kids who
are going to outperform us

00:09:02.020 --> 00:09:03.957 align:middle line:90%
at school when we're at school.

00:09:03.957 --> 00:09:06.760 align:middle line:84%
You know, what happens if
we're at the bottom of the bell

00:09:06.760 --> 00:09:07.260 align:middle line:90%
curve?

00:09:07.260 --> 00:09:11.466 align:middle line:84%
And these days in education,
they list who's, you know,

00:09:11.466 --> 00:09:12.840 align:middle line:84%
if you're in
medical school, they

00:09:12.840 --> 00:09:16.590 align:middle line:84%
list where you are in the
whole league basically.

00:09:16.590 --> 00:09:19.090 align:middle line:84%
And if you're in the
bottom, you know.

00:09:19.090 --> 00:09:22.070 align:middle line:84%
And it's, as I say,
your neighborhood.

00:09:22.070 --> 00:09:25.710 align:middle line:84%
That's become a ground of one
upmanship and competition.

00:09:25.710 --> 00:09:31.140 align:middle line:84%
Everything we do is
framed by competition.

00:09:31.140 --> 00:09:33.990 align:middle line:84%
Our conversations
with people are

00:09:33.990 --> 00:09:36.300 align:middle line:84%
very much about
picking the flaws

00:09:36.300 --> 00:09:38.300 align:middle line:90%
in someone else's arguments.

00:09:38.300 --> 00:09:41.660 align:middle line:84%
If somebody disagrees
with us, we're

00:09:41.660 --> 00:09:44.430 align:middle line:84%
taught, essentially,
to demonize them

00:09:44.430 --> 00:09:46.980 align:middle line:84%
but also to pulverize
them, to try

00:09:46.980 --> 00:09:50.090 align:middle line:84%
to destroy them
through our arguments.

00:09:50.090 --> 00:09:52.920 align:middle line:84%
The whole idea is about
being right, being first,

00:09:52.920 --> 00:09:54.320 align:middle line:90%
being individual.

00:09:54.320 --> 00:09:56.700 align:middle line:90%
That's been our programming.

00:09:56.700 --> 00:10:00.680 align:middle line:84%
If we have a hard drive, it's
been programmed with I win,

00:10:00.680 --> 00:10:01.870 align:middle line:90%
you lose.

00:10:01.870 --> 00:10:07.510 align:middle line:84%
And so what I'm saying is this
is absolutely against nature.

00:10:07.510 --> 00:10:09.750 align:middle line:84%
And that's why we're
in the mess we're in.

00:10:09.750 --> 00:10:12.390 align:middle line:84%
This is what selfish
looks like now.

00:10:12.390 --> 00:10:15.974 align:middle line:84%
Selfish looks like the breakdown
of every aspect of our society.

00:10:15.974 --> 00:10:17.890 align:middle line:84%
And that's what we're
going through right now.

00:10:17.890 --> 00:10:19.306 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: You're
absolutely right.

00:10:19.306 --> 00:10:21.300 align:middle line:84%
And I think one
very mundane example

00:10:21.300 --> 00:10:24.790 align:middle line:84%
of that is in America
certainly, road rage.

00:10:24.790 --> 00:10:27.930 align:middle line:84%
I don't dare-- in California,
I don't dare signal

00:10:27.930 --> 00:10:30.570 align:middle line:84%
to let anyone know I'm coming
into their lane anymore.

00:10:30.570 --> 00:10:33.710 align:middle line:84%
I just wait until I feel there's
a safe opportunity and go.

00:10:33.710 --> 00:10:38.640 align:middle line:84%
Because if you signal,
that is a direct assault

00:10:38.640 --> 00:10:40.560 align:middle line:90%
to the other person's space.

00:10:40.560 --> 00:10:41.740 align:middle line:90%
And they'll speed up.

00:10:41.740 --> 00:10:42.750 align:middle line:90%
I mean, this is common.

00:10:42.750 --> 00:10:44.270 align:middle line:90%
This is just common.

00:10:44.270 --> 00:10:46.680 align:middle line:84%
I was in traffic school once,
and I told them no, I never

00:10:46.680 --> 00:10:47.180 align:middle line:90%
signal.

00:10:47.180 --> 00:10:48.260 align:middle line:90%
And I told them why.

00:10:48.260 --> 00:10:50.550 align:middle line:84%
And the other people are
saying, yeah, you're right.

00:10:50.550 --> 00:10:52.630 align:middle line:84%
So that is how
fundamental it is.

00:10:52.630 --> 00:10:55.690 align:middle line:84%
We can't even let someone have
a little space on the road,

00:10:55.690 --> 00:10:58.291 align:middle line:84%
as though we own that
space just ahead.

00:10:58.291 --> 00:10:58.790 align:middle line:90%
That's sick.

00:10:58.790 --> 00:10:59.790 align:middle line:90%
>>MCTAGGART: Absolutely.

00:10:59.790 --> 00:11:00.350 align:middle line:90%
Absolutely.

00:11:00.350 --> 00:11:04.550 align:middle line:84%
But it's just become the
mindset that, as I say,

00:11:04.550 --> 00:11:07.390 align:middle line:84%
pretty much dictates
everything we do.

00:11:07.390 --> 00:11:11.370 align:middle line:84%
And so we have this big problem
on a giant collective level,

00:11:11.370 --> 00:11:14.510 align:middle line:84%
and we have this problem
on an individual level.

00:11:14.510 --> 00:11:16.940 align:middle line:84%
And it wasn't supposed
to be like this.

00:11:16.940 --> 00:11:21.370 align:middle line:84%
And in fact, when we
start living according

00:11:21.370 --> 00:11:25.210 align:middle line:84%
to the definition of who we
really are, and start wiping

00:11:25.210 --> 00:11:28.800 align:middle line:84%
that hard drive clean,
only then will we

00:11:28.800 --> 00:11:30.790 align:middle line:90%
evolve to another level.

00:11:30.790 --> 00:11:31.610 align:middle line:90%
Only then.

00:11:31.610 --> 00:11:34.110 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And you say it's
about the last 250 years,

00:11:34.110 --> 00:11:36.380 align:middle line:84%
right, since this
paradigm has really

00:11:36.380 --> 00:11:39.212 align:middle line:84%
taken hold within our
psyche, maybe even less.

00:11:39.212 --> 00:11:39.920 align:middle line:90%
>>MCTAGGART: Yes.

00:11:39.920 --> 00:11:42.580 align:middle line:84%
I mean, there've always
been cases of people wanting

00:11:42.580 --> 00:11:44.660 align:middle line:90%
to be aggressive, or whatever.

00:11:44.660 --> 00:11:48.560 align:middle line:84%
Or societies where
people were in charge.

00:11:48.560 --> 00:11:51.490 align:middle line:84%
But prior to Newton,
we had much more

00:11:51.490 --> 00:11:55.650 align:middle line:84%
of a holistic view of ourselves
in relation to the cosmos.

00:11:55.650 --> 00:11:58.780 align:middle line:84%
Newton really essentially
ripped us out of that

00:11:58.780 --> 00:12:03.090 align:middle line:84%
and created a world
of individual things,

00:12:03.090 --> 00:12:05.320 align:middle line:90%
and really defined thingness.

00:12:05.320 --> 00:12:08.320 align:middle line:84%
And so it became a real
understanding of ours

00:12:08.320 --> 00:12:11.780 align:middle line:84%
that we end with the hair
on our skin, at which point

00:12:11.780 --> 00:12:13.590 align:middle line:90%
the rest of the universe begins.

00:12:13.590 --> 00:12:16.890 align:middle line:84%
And that, you know,
it's hard to understand

00:12:16.890 --> 00:12:20.150 align:middle line:84%
how much that
definition of ourselves

00:12:20.150 --> 00:12:25.100 align:middle line:84%
really informs how we operate,
because not all cultures do.

00:12:25.100 --> 00:12:28.720 align:middle line:84%
Many indigenous cultures
think very differently.

00:12:28.720 --> 00:12:32.060 align:middle line:84%
They think of themselves
as being all connected.

00:12:32.060 --> 00:12:36.345 align:middle line:84%
And from that, they create a
very different kind of society.

00:12:36.345 --> 00:12:37.220 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Absolutely.

00:12:37.220 --> 00:12:39.436 align:middle line:84%
And quantum physics,
in this sense.

00:12:39.436 --> 00:12:41.060 align:middle line:84%
Really, when you
started doing research

00:12:41.060 --> 00:12:44.030 align:middle line:84%
for this book, where else can
you go but quantum physics

00:12:44.030 --> 00:12:46.650 align:middle line:84%
if you're going to look for
innate interconnectedness.

00:12:46.650 --> 00:12:49.390 align:middle line:84%
And you really, I think you
lay out the story very well.

00:12:49.390 --> 00:12:52.040 align:middle line:84%
And let's get into a
little bit about some

00:12:52.040 --> 00:12:54.210 align:middle line:84%
of the physics of
entanglement behind this,

00:12:54.210 --> 00:12:55.590 align:middle line:90%
without doing the whole thing.

00:12:55.590 --> 00:12:57.860 align:middle line:84%
I've done a couple other
interviews on entanglement

00:12:57.860 --> 00:12:59.680 align:middle line:84%
that people can go
to in the archives.

00:12:59.680 --> 00:13:02.610 align:middle line:84%
But for the purposes of
setting this up right now,

00:13:02.610 --> 00:13:04.000 align:middle line:90%
let's do a little bit on it.

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:04.666 align:middle line:90%
>>MCTAGGART: OK.

00:13:04.666 --> 00:13:09.240 align:middle line:84%
Well, fundamentally, I mean our
idea about subatomic particles

00:13:09.240 --> 00:13:12.800 align:middle line:84%
are, as physics class has shown
us, little billiard balls.

00:13:12.800 --> 00:13:14.520 align:middle line:84%
You know, that's
what we think of.

00:13:14.520 --> 00:13:17.800 align:middle line:84%
But actually, a subatomic
particle is not that.

00:13:17.800 --> 00:13:22.760 align:middle line:84%
It's a vibrating packet of
energy, trading information

00:13:22.760 --> 00:13:26.620 align:middle line:84%
and energy with other subatomic
particles and this background

00:13:26.620 --> 00:13:27.820 align:middle line:90%
energy field.

00:13:27.820 --> 00:13:31.630 align:middle line:84%
So a subatomic particle is
essentially a shape shifter.

00:13:31.630 --> 00:13:36.890 align:middle line:84%
So when you look down at
matter at that tiny level, what

00:13:36.890 --> 00:13:41.680 align:middle line:84%
you find is there's no
such thing as a thing.

00:13:41.680 --> 00:13:44.140 align:middle line:84%
The unit of the
universe isn't a thing.

00:13:44.140 --> 00:13:45.500 align:middle line:90%
It's a relationship.

00:13:45.500 --> 00:13:48.870 align:middle line:84%
It's the relationship between
those subatomic particles.

00:13:48.870 --> 00:13:51.530 align:middle line:84%
And the other thing, as you
said, about subatomic particles

00:13:51.530 --> 00:13:54.770 align:middle line:84%
is once they're in
contact, you can move one

00:13:54.770 --> 00:13:58.390 align:middle line:84%
to New York and the
other one to Australia,

00:13:58.390 --> 00:14:01.660 align:middle line:84%
and they will continue to
be informed by each other.

00:14:01.660 --> 00:14:04.767 align:middle line:84%
Imagine they're twins
separated at birth.

00:14:04.767 --> 00:14:06.600 align:middle line:84%
Even though they never
see each other again,

00:14:06.600 --> 00:14:10.920 align:middle line:84%
because they were in contact--
let's say they're boys.

00:14:10.920 --> 00:14:13.540 align:middle line:84%
They both marry a
woman called Jane.

00:14:13.540 --> 00:14:15.670 align:middle line:90%
They both love the color blue.

00:14:15.670 --> 00:14:18.020 align:middle line:84%
And if one falls down
and breaks his leg,

00:14:18.020 --> 00:14:20.160 align:middle line:84%
the other one falls down
at the exact same moment

00:14:20.160 --> 00:14:22.035 align:middle line:84%
and breaks his leg too,
even though he's just

00:14:22.035 --> 00:14:24.660 align:middle line:84%
sitting there sipping
a latte in Starbucks.

00:14:24.660 --> 00:14:27.220 align:middle line:84%
So that's what a subatomic--
that's what entanglement

00:14:27.220 --> 00:14:28.110 align:middle line:90%
is essentially.

00:14:28.110 --> 00:14:30.850 align:middle line:84%
It's constantly being
affected by each other

00:14:30.850 --> 00:14:33.620 align:middle line:90%
over any time and any distance.

00:14:33.620 --> 00:14:36.190 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And this isn't
just in the human population.

00:14:36.190 --> 00:14:38.030 align:middle line:84%
We have, I believe,
Clive Backster, right.

00:14:38.030 --> 00:14:39.070 align:middle line:90%
We have his work.

00:14:39.070 --> 00:14:40.220 align:middle line:90%
Is it Clive or Cleve?

00:14:40.220 --> 00:14:40.560 align:middle line:90%
>>MCTAGGART: Cleve.

00:14:40.560 --> 00:14:41.310 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Cleve.

00:14:41.310 --> 00:14:43.143 align:middle line:84%
I always forget whether
it's Cleve or Clive.

00:14:43.143 --> 00:14:45.410 align:middle line:84%
His work with plants
and the same thing.

00:14:45.410 --> 00:14:48.550 align:middle line:84%
The fields effect on plants
on an emotional level,

00:14:48.550 --> 00:14:50.740 align:middle line:90%
plants responding to emotion.

00:14:50.740 --> 00:14:52.730 align:middle line:84%
We also have the work
by Rupert Sheldrake

00:14:52.730 --> 00:14:57.502 align:middle line:84%
about dogs who know when
their owners are coming home.

00:14:57.502 --> 00:14:58.210 align:middle line:90%
>>MCTAGGART: Yes.

00:14:58.210 --> 00:15:02.100 align:middle line:84%
I mean, when you start
factoring in both non-locality

00:15:02.100 --> 00:15:05.120 align:middle line:84%
and the whole idea of
a quantum energy field,

00:15:05.120 --> 00:15:08.160 align:middle line:84%
then that is a
wonderful, neat metaphor

00:15:08.160 --> 00:15:11.590 align:middle line:84%
to understand things
that-- connections

00:15:11.590 --> 00:15:15.310 align:middle line:84%
that occur between people or
between people and other living

00:15:15.310 --> 00:15:19.320 align:middle line:84%
things like plants across
time and across space.

00:15:19.320 --> 00:15:22.045 align:middle line:84%
That makes sense only
by factoring in a field.

00:15:22.045 --> 00:15:22.920 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Absolutely.

00:15:22.920 --> 00:15:25.360 align:middle line:84%
And in your book, there's a
couple of really cute bits

00:15:25.360 --> 00:15:27.800 align:middle line:84%
where you talk about
your dog, Ollie.

00:15:27.800 --> 00:15:29.940 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I would
love to meet Ollie.

00:15:29.940 --> 00:15:32.200 align:middle line:84%
He sounds like quite a
character, a curmudgeon on one

00:15:32.200 --> 00:15:34.740 align:middle line:84%
hand and in another,
very generous.

00:15:34.740 --> 00:15:38.070 align:middle line:84%
>>MCTAGGART: Well, Ollie is--
Ollie was also an inspiration.

00:15:38.070 --> 00:15:40.880 align:middle line:84%
He, by the way, has gone on
to the kennel into the sky.

00:15:40.880 --> 00:15:41.740 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Aw, when
did that happen?

00:15:41.740 --> 00:15:42.573 align:middle line:90%
>>MCTAGGART: I know.

00:15:42.573 --> 00:15:44.810 align:middle line:90%
Just last September, sadly.

00:15:44.810 --> 00:15:45.460 align:middle line:90%
I know.

00:15:45.460 --> 00:15:47.710 align:middle line:90%
He was a darling.

00:15:47.710 --> 00:15:49.550 align:middle line:90%
He was a total character.

00:15:49.550 --> 00:15:52.970 align:middle line:84%
He's a Cavalier, King Ch-- he
was a Cavalier King Charles

00:15:52.970 --> 00:15:53.530 align:middle line:90%
Spaniel.

00:15:53.530 --> 00:15:55.950 align:middle line:84%
And they were bred
by royal decree.

00:15:55.950 --> 00:15:58.320 align:middle line:84%
And consequently,
a lot of that breed

00:15:58.320 --> 00:16:01.710 align:middle line:90%
are extremely sort of haughty.

00:16:01.710 --> 00:16:03.340 align:middle line:90%
They're very regal.

00:16:03.340 --> 00:16:06.240 align:middle line:84%
And Ollie was the
exception to the rule

00:16:06.240 --> 00:16:09.750 align:middle line:84%
in terms of dogs that know
when their owners come home.

00:16:09.750 --> 00:16:12.840 align:middle line:84%
Ollie knew when we were coming
home and could care less.

00:16:12.840 --> 00:16:15.010 align:middle line:84%
But Ollie was really
interesting for me,

00:16:15.010 --> 00:16:19.340 align:middle line:84%
because even though he didn't
have much time for humans,

00:16:19.340 --> 00:16:22.010 align:middle line:84%
Ollie was kind to
every dog on his walk.

00:16:22.010 --> 00:16:24.860 align:middle line:84%
And I watched him with our
next door neighbor, T-Bone,

00:16:24.860 --> 00:16:27.490 align:middle line:84%
who is a little girl
Affenpinscher, tiny little dog,

00:16:27.490 --> 00:16:28.590 align:middle line:90%
even smaller than him.

00:16:28.590 --> 00:16:30.680 align:middle line:84%
Ollie used to dig
holes under our fence

00:16:30.680 --> 00:16:33.830 align:middle line:84%
and stick bones under
there for T-Bone.

00:16:33.830 --> 00:16:37.390 align:middle line:84%
And when she came over, he
would raid our garbage bin

00:16:37.390 --> 00:16:40.040 align:middle line:84%
to find a chicken
carcass for her.

00:16:40.040 --> 00:16:42.270 align:middle line:84%
And he would let her
have his food first.

00:16:42.270 --> 00:16:44.140 align:middle line:84%
And he would roll
over and let her

00:16:44.140 --> 00:16:46.440 align:middle line:84%
win when they were
rough housing, just

00:16:46.440 --> 00:16:47.870 align:middle line:90%
to keep her in the game.

00:16:47.870 --> 00:16:50.450 align:middle line:84%
And I kept looking
at this and saying,

00:16:50.450 --> 00:16:52.780 align:middle line:84%
this isn't survival
of the fittest.

00:16:52.780 --> 00:16:54.190 align:middle line:90%
This isn't dog-eat-dog.

00:16:54.190 --> 00:16:57.120 align:middle line:84%
There's nothing dog-eat-dog
about Ollie's world.

00:16:57.120 --> 00:17:00.870 align:middle line:84%
You know he's a very
cooperative entity.

00:17:00.870 --> 00:17:04.960 align:middle line:84%
And so that also started me
thinking was Darwin right?

00:17:04.960 --> 00:17:09.657 align:middle line:84%
And again, the answer is,
overwhelmingly, he wasn't.

00:17:09.657 --> 00:17:10.490 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: He wasn't.

00:17:10.490 --> 00:17:14.031 align:middle line:84%
And OK, you say he could care
less when people came home.

00:17:14.031 --> 00:17:15.780 align:middle line:84%
But he did care if you
picked up his leash

00:17:15.780 --> 00:17:17.470 align:middle line:84%
or even thought about
his leash, right.

00:17:17.470 --> 00:17:19.490 align:middle line:84%
He was ready to go
if it was a walk.

00:17:19.490 --> 00:17:19.750 align:middle line:90%
>>MCTAGGART: Absolutely.

00:17:19.750 --> 00:17:21.550 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: He caught
the field on that one.

00:17:21.550 --> 00:17:24.369 align:middle line:84%
He was just not interested
in the rest of it.

00:17:24.369 --> 00:17:27.450 align:middle line:84%
You just said something a
moment ago about Darwin.

00:17:27.450 --> 00:17:32.800 align:middle line:84%
And when I've read some
various analysis of his work

00:17:32.800 --> 00:17:35.020 align:middle line:90%
in the later part of his life.

00:17:35.020 --> 00:17:37.310 align:middle line:84%
And some of it has
indicated-- most of it

00:17:37.310 --> 00:17:40.210 align:middle line:84%
has indicated that he actually
had a change of heart.

00:17:40.210 --> 00:17:43.710 align:middle line:84%
He was under the influence
of another academic early

00:17:43.710 --> 00:17:45.860 align:middle line:84%
in his life, and
he started buying

00:17:45.860 --> 00:17:49.380 align:middle line:84%
into this concept of
competition and life is war.

00:17:49.380 --> 00:17:50.884 align:middle line:90%
That's not where he ended up.

00:17:50.884 --> 00:17:51.550 align:middle line:90%
>>MCTAGGART: No.

00:17:51.550 --> 00:17:58.430 align:middle line:84%
He became much more aware of
and appreciative of cooperation

00:17:58.430 --> 00:17:59.610 align:middle line:90%
later in his life.

00:17:59.610 --> 00:18:02.170 align:middle line:84%
But early in-- he was
a man of his time.

00:18:02.170 --> 00:18:05.730 align:middle line:84%
And the time, at the time,
there was a lot of worry

00:18:05.730 --> 00:18:07.910 align:middle line:84%
about population
explosion and the idea

00:18:07.910 --> 00:18:09.910 align:middle line:84%
that there wasn't
enough to go around.

00:18:09.910 --> 00:18:12.890 align:middle line:84%
And he started thinking
about that and thought, yes.

00:18:12.890 --> 00:18:15.790 align:middle line:84%
Life must proceed and
evolve through struggle.

00:18:15.790 --> 00:18:18.280 align:middle line:84%
It must be a race
to the finish line.

00:18:18.280 --> 00:18:20.700 align:middle line:90%
And that really informed him.

00:18:20.700 --> 00:18:22.886 align:middle line:84%
He never actually came
up with the term survival

00:18:22.886 --> 00:18:23.510 align:middle line:90%
of the fittest.

00:18:23.510 --> 00:18:24.680 align:middle line:90%
That was a friend of his.

00:18:24.680 --> 00:18:25.000 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:26.375 align:middle line:84%
>>MCTAGGART: But
his ideas really

00:18:26.375 --> 00:18:30.960 align:middle line:84%
swept the globe, thanks to
the advent of mass printing.

00:18:30.960 --> 00:18:39.230 align:middle line:84%
And again, it's impossible to
over-appreciate Darwin's effect

00:18:39.230 --> 00:18:42.050 align:middle line:90%
on so many areas of society.

00:18:42.050 --> 00:18:44.190 align:middle line:84%
He really became a
justifying principle

00:18:44.190 --> 00:18:48.600 align:middle line:84%
for burgeoning industrial
capitalism, you know.

00:18:48.600 --> 00:18:53.720 align:middle line:84%
He became a justifying
principle for colonialism,

00:18:53.720 --> 00:18:57.230 align:middle line:84%
one race taking over
another for its own good.

00:18:57.230 --> 00:19:00.220 align:middle line:84%
He became a justifying principle
for sociopathic behavior.

00:19:00.220 --> 00:19:01.630 align:middle line:90%
Hitler loved Darwin.

00:19:01.630 --> 00:19:04.960 align:middle line:84%
You know, he was
just-- and that really

00:19:04.960 --> 00:19:07.760 align:middle line:84%
became our defining
model in a lot of ways

00:19:07.760 --> 00:19:10.420 align:middle line:90%
for our modern society.

00:19:10.420 --> 00:19:13.360 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And yet, I will give
you an example of cooperation.

00:19:13.360 --> 00:19:14.820 align:middle line:90%
Let's go to the other extreme.

00:19:14.820 --> 00:19:17.660 align:middle line:84%
My son went to the Waldorf
School in Sacramento

00:19:17.660 --> 00:19:21.230 align:middle line:84%
and had this wonderful
teacher named Mr. Murray.

00:19:21.230 --> 00:19:22.572 align:middle line:90%
And you know the Waldorf system?

00:19:22.572 --> 00:19:23.530 align:middle line:90%
>>MCTAGGART: Very well.

00:19:23.530 --> 00:19:24.480 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes, right.

00:19:24.480 --> 00:19:27.299 align:middle line:84%
And so the children have to
have direct communication

00:19:27.299 --> 00:19:28.840 align:middle line:84%
and relationship
with their teachers.

00:19:28.840 --> 00:19:30.770 align:middle line:84%
You shake hands going
in in the morning.

00:19:30.770 --> 00:19:32.400 align:middle line:90%
You shake hands going out.

00:19:32.400 --> 00:19:34.640 align:middle line:84%
But one thing that Mr.
Murray did with the class,

00:19:34.640 --> 00:19:36.570 align:middle line:84%
first through eighth,
those eight years

00:19:36.570 --> 00:19:41.250 align:middle line:84%
they're together, and--
is that he encouraged

00:19:41.250 --> 00:19:44.290 align:middle line:84%
them to help each
other, even on tests.

00:19:44.290 --> 00:19:46.190 align:middle line:84%
Not only that, but
with everything.

00:19:46.190 --> 00:19:49.040 align:middle line:84%
His feeling was if
you're lagging behind,

00:19:49.040 --> 00:19:52.580 align:middle line:84%
then have someone who
understands the subject well

00:19:52.580 --> 00:19:54.440 align:middle line:84%
help you out so
that everyone can

00:19:54.440 --> 00:19:56.140 align:middle line:90%
thrive within the classroom.

00:19:56.140 --> 00:19:58.240 align:middle line:84%
And watching what
happened over the years

00:19:58.240 --> 00:20:00.240 align:middle line:84%
with that group of
individuals was amazing.

00:20:00.240 --> 00:20:03.200 align:middle line:84%
I mean, most of them are quite
successful in their own right

00:20:03.200 --> 00:20:06.590 align:middle line:84%
at each of the different, widely
varied things they're doing.

00:20:06.590 --> 00:20:09.940 align:middle line:84%
But this is an example
where competition would not

00:20:09.940 --> 00:20:11.500 align:middle line:90%
have helped that group.

00:20:11.500 --> 00:20:13.650 align:middle line:84%
>>MCTAGGART: No, and
the studies looking

00:20:13.650 --> 00:20:19.760 align:middle line:84%
at everything from
education to business models

00:20:19.760 --> 00:20:24.460 align:middle line:84%
demonstrate that competition is
a dangerous and outmoded model

00:20:24.460 --> 00:20:26.780 align:middle line:90%
in many areas of our society.

00:20:26.780 --> 00:20:30.680 align:middle line:84%
Studies looking at students,
where A students are working

00:20:30.680 --> 00:20:33.090 align:middle line:84%
side by side with
C students, find

00:20:33.090 --> 00:20:36.150 align:middle line:84%
that both the A students
and the C students

00:20:36.150 --> 00:20:39.820 align:middle line:84%
do better by working together,
rather than being streamed

00:20:39.820 --> 00:20:42.820 align:middle line:84%
and pitted against each
other competitively.

00:20:42.820 --> 00:20:45.090 align:middle line:90%
Business-wise, the same thing.

00:20:45.090 --> 00:20:47.690 align:middle line:84%
I spoke to Jack
Canfield recently,

00:20:47.690 --> 00:20:53.030 align:middle line:84%
and he was telling me about how
one company he went to work for

00:20:53.030 --> 00:20:58.370 align:middle line:84%
had this very-- they had little
silos of groups of people

00:20:58.370 --> 00:21:02.310 align:middle line:84%
within the organization working
competitively with each other.

00:21:02.310 --> 00:21:04.270 align:middle line:84%
And this created such
a climate of fear

00:21:04.270 --> 00:21:07.320 align:middle line:84%
that it inhibited
innovation, compared

00:21:07.320 --> 00:21:11.080 align:middle line:84%
to their rival,
another company which

00:21:11.080 --> 00:21:15.310 align:middle line:84%
had the team work together as
the whole, the organization

00:21:15.310 --> 00:21:16.910 align:middle line:84%
worked together
as a whole, and be

00:21:16.910 --> 00:21:19.404 align:middle line:90%
rewarded as a whole for success.

00:21:19.404 --> 00:21:21.570 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Very discreet of
you not to mention names.

00:21:21.570 --> 00:21:23.580 align:middle line:84%
Very well known, very
large corporations.

00:21:23.580 --> 00:21:27.050 align:middle line:84%
And that was a very interesting
experience and observation

00:21:27.050 --> 00:21:27.579 align:middle line:90%
on his part.

00:21:27.579 --> 00:21:28.870 align:middle line:90%
And of course, you can feel it.

00:21:28.870 --> 00:21:31.830 align:middle line:84%
When you have that fear going,
creativity simply cannot

00:21:31.830 --> 00:21:32.660 align:middle line:90%
thrive.

00:21:32.660 --> 00:21:34.920 align:middle line:84%
And then when you have
extreme fear going on,

00:21:34.920 --> 00:21:36.880 align:middle line:84%
you get something that
looks like Columbine.

00:21:36.880 --> 00:21:38.610 align:middle line:84%
And you wrote about this
a little bit in your book.

00:21:38.610 --> 00:21:39.150 align:middle line:90%
>>MCTAGGART: Yes.

00:21:39.150 --> 00:21:41.000 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: The t-shirt
on one of the shooters.

00:21:41.000 --> 00:21:42.541 align:middle line:84%
>>MCTAGGART: Well,
this is the thing.

00:21:42.541 --> 00:21:46.640 align:middle line:84%
Again, sociopathic behavior
looks to Darwinian stuff.

00:21:46.640 --> 00:21:49.630 align:middle line:84%
There are big websites
now that are all

00:21:49.630 --> 00:21:56.550 align:middle line:84%
about culling the population
of the lesser mortals.

00:21:56.550 --> 00:22:00.281 align:middle line:84%
And of the two shooters who
walked into Columbine High

00:22:00.281 --> 00:22:02.530 align:middle line:84%
and started blowing away
their classmates, one of them

00:22:02.530 --> 00:22:05.960 align:middle line:84%
was wearing a t-shirt that
said, "natural selection."

00:22:05.960 --> 00:22:10.480 align:middle line:84%
So that's the extremes to
which this idea goes to.

00:22:10.480 --> 00:22:12.820 align:middle line:84%
And it was, you know,
it happened at the time

00:22:12.820 --> 00:22:13.490 align:middle line:90%
with Darwin.

00:22:13.490 --> 00:22:20.540 align:middle line:84%
There was a great deal of
eugenics and that whole idea

00:22:20.540 --> 00:22:24.650 align:middle line:84%
of getting rid of
the sub normal.

00:22:24.650 --> 00:22:26.290 align:middle line:90%
And it was now justified.

00:22:26.290 --> 00:22:29.330 align:middle line:84%
There was a justifying
principle for it.

00:22:29.330 --> 00:22:31.080 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Very sad but true.

00:22:31.080 --> 00:22:34.210 align:middle line:84%
Let's talk, again going back
to pop culture and the movie,

00:22:34.210 --> 00:22:38.570 align:middle line:84%
"A Beautiful Mind," John Nash,
who the movie was based on,

00:22:38.570 --> 00:22:43.850 align:middle line:84%
a real character in life,
played by Russell Crowe.

00:22:43.850 --> 00:22:46.660 align:middle line:84%
Let's talk about that
scene where he laid out

00:22:46.660 --> 00:22:52.310 align:middle line:84%
a case mathematically for
cooperation versus competition,

00:22:52.310 --> 00:22:53.990 align:middle line:84%
when all of the guys
were essentially

00:22:53.990 --> 00:22:56.690 align:middle line:84%
lusting after a blonde
girl who was surrounded

00:22:56.690 --> 00:22:58.534 align:middle line:90%
by her brunette girlfriends.

00:22:58.534 --> 00:22:59.200 align:middle line:90%
>>MCTAGGART: OK.

00:22:59.200 --> 00:23:03.380 align:middle line:84%
Well, this iconic
scene in that movie

00:23:03.380 --> 00:23:06.180 align:middle line:84%
has to do with-- you know, Nash
is a post graduate student,

00:23:06.180 --> 00:23:09.610 align:middle line:84%
and he's there with his
economist student friends.

00:23:09.610 --> 00:23:12.610 align:middle line:84%
And they're in the bar, and
a blonde and her friends,

00:23:12.610 --> 00:23:14.450 align:middle line:90%
her brunette friends, walk in.

00:23:14.450 --> 00:23:18.220 align:middle line:84%
And the boys are all sort of
deciding, saying, OK guys.

00:23:18.220 --> 00:23:22.440 align:middle line:84%
As Adam Smith says, we
do best for everyone

00:23:22.440 --> 00:23:24.280 align:middle line:84%
by looking after
number one, you know.

00:23:24.280 --> 00:23:26.260 align:middle line:90%
It's every man for himself here.

00:23:26.260 --> 00:23:29.170 align:middle line:84%
And Nash sort of is
shaking his head.

00:23:29.170 --> 00:23:31.840 align:middle line:90%
And he finally says, no.

00:23:31.840 --> 00:23:33.790 align:middle line:84%
Because if we all
go for the blonde,

00:23:33.790 --> 00:23:35.320 align:middle line:90%
we're going to block each other.

00:23:35.320 --> 00:23:37.170 align:middle line:90%
And no one will get her.

00:23:37.170 --> 00:23:39.840 align:middle line:84%
But if we go to
her friends then,

00:23:39.840 --> 00:23:41.620 align:middle line:84%
they won't want
anything to do with us

00:23:41.620 --> 00:23:43.900 align:middle line:84%
because no one wants
to be second best.

00:23:43.900 --> 00:23:46.420 align:middle line:84%
So what if no one
goes for the blonde,

00:23:46.420 --> 00:23:47.941 align:middle line:90%
and we all go to her friends.

00:23:47.941 --> 00:23:50.190 align:middle line:84%
Well, this is the only way
we're going to have a date.

00:23:50.190 --> 00:23:51.861 align:middle line:90%
This is the only way we all win.

00:23:51.861 --> 00:23:53.360 align:middle line:84%
And then he starts
thinking about it

00:23:53.360 --> 00:23:56.630 align:middle line:84%
and he goes, you know,
Adam Smith, what he said

00:23:56.630 --> 00:23:58.290 align:middle line:90%
was incomplete.

00:23:58.290 --> 00:24:01.250 align:middle line:84%
It's not that the
individual does best

00:24:01.250 --> 00:24:02.830 align:middle line:90%
by looking after number one.

00:24:02.830 --> 00:24:06.750 align:middle line:84%
The individual does best, the
best response to any situation

00:24:06.750 --> 00:24:10.370 align:middle line:84%
is what's best for the
individual and the group.

00:24:10.370 --> 00:24:12.750 align:middle line:90%
And with that, he walks out.

00:24:12.750 --> 00:24:14.900 align:middle line:90%
He says, Adam Smith was wrong.

00:24:14.900 --> 00:24:18.270 align:middle line:84%
And he goes, governing dynamics,
runs out, and thanks the blonde

00:24:18.270 --> 00:24:20.514 align:middle line:84%
for being the muse to
the theory that ended up

00:24:20.514 --> 00:24:21.680 align:middle line:90%
winning him the Nobel Prize.

00:24:21.680 --> 00:24:22.554 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Absolutely.

00:24:22.554 --> 00:24:23.730 align:middle line:90%
I love that story.

00:24:23.730 --> 00:24:25.470 align:middle line:90%
Very practical.

00:24:25.470 --> 00:24:28.310 align:middle line:84%
But a beautiful mind to be able
to put those pieces together

00:24:28.310 --> 00:24:29.040 align:middle line:90%
for us now.

00:24:29.040 --> 00:24:32.240 align:middle line:84%
And you have woven this
together with its impact

00:24:32.240 --> 00:24:34.100 align:middle line:84%
not just on whether you
get the babe or not,

00:24:34.100 --> 00:24:37.140 align:middle line:84%
but also onto our physical
health, our relationships

00:24:37.140 --> 00:24:39.210 align:middle line:84%
with each other, our
families, and so forth.

00:24:39.210 --> 00:24:40.814 align:middle line:84%
And just before--
we're going to take

00:24:40.814 --> 00:24:41.980 align:middle line:90%
a break in a couple minutes.

00:24:41.980 --> 00:24:44.220 align:middle line:84%
But before that, let's
introduce the subject

00:24:44.220 --> 00:24:48.180 align:middle line:84%
of Japanese individuals, the
Japanese culture, and heart

00:24:48.180 --> 00:24:49.820 align:middle line:90%
health.

00:24:49.820 --> 00:24:50.850 align:middle line:90%
I find it fascinating.

00:24:50.850 --> 00:24:53.260 align:middle line:84%
>>MCTAGGART: Well, you know
what's really interesting.

00:24:53.260 --> 00:24:56.500 align:middle line:84%
Again, we have this
idea that the whole idea

00:24:56.500 --> 00:24:59.960 align:middle line:84%
of the individual being
that what's best for us

00:24:59.960 --> 00:25:04.660 align:middle line:84%
is really promoting our own
life, and our own needs,

00:25:04.660 --> 00:25:07.240 align:middle line:90%
and looking out for number one.

00:25:07.240 --> 00:25:10.080 align:middle line:84%
But studies of the
Japanese have found

00:25:10.080 --> 00:25:12.540 align:middle line:90%
something really fascinating.

00:25:12.540 --> 00:25:15.660 align:middle line:84%
Epidemiologists, people
who look at populations,

00:25:15.660 --> 00:25:18.890 align:middle line:84%
have looked at what happens to
the Japanese when they move.

00:25:18.890 --> 00:25:21.830 align:middle line:84%
Because the Japanese are
a really strange culture.

00:25:21.830 --> 00:25:24.330 align:middle line:84%
They smoke like chimneys, but
they don't have heart disease.

00:25:24.330 --> 00:25:25.390 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:25:25.390 --> 00:25:30.060 align:middle line:84%
>>MCTAGGART: So-- except
when they come to the US.

00:25:30.060 --> 00:25:32.810 align:middle line:84%
And some of them
get heart disease

00:25:32.810 --> 00:25:36.670 align:middle line:84%
that mimics just like the
rest of the population.

00:25:36.670 --> 00:25:39.170 align:middle line:84%
So these scientists
started studying this.

00:25:39.170 --> 00:25:42.810 align:middle line:84%
And they found that
among those who

00:25:42.810 --> 00:25:46.500 align:middle line:84%
didn't get heart disease, even
though they moved to America--

00:25:46.500 --> 00:25:48.340 align:middle line:90%
it was really fascinating.

00:25:48.340 --> 00:25:50.450 align:middle line:90%
It had nothing to do with diet.

00:25:50.450 --> 00:25:54.315 align:middle line:84%
It didn't matter whether they
ate a Big Mac and fries or tofu

00:25:54.315 --> 00:25:55.920 align:middle line:90%
and sushi.

00:25:55.920 --> 00:25:58.170 align:middle line:84%
What mattered, the only
thing that mattered,

00:25:58.170 --> 00:26:01.600 align:middle line:84%
was whether or not they
kept close social groups

00:26:01.600 --> 00:26:05.540 align:middle line:84%
that they had similar to what
they had in the old country.

00:26:05.540 --> 00:26:06.400 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:26:06.400 --> 00:26:08.180 align:middle line:84%
>>MCTAGGART: So
these scientists,

00:26:08.180 --> 00:26:10.650 align:middle line:84%
these epidemiologists,
traveled to Japan

00:26:10.650 --> 00:26:12.735 align:middle line:90%
to try to find the X factor.

00:26:12.735 --> 00:26:16.350 align:middle line:84%
You know, what was the
missing X factor of health?

00:26:16.350 --> 00:26:20.820 align:middle line:84%
Why would that be a
buffer to ill health.

00:26:20.820 --> 00:26:22.950 align:middle line:84%
And the Japanese looked
at them and said well,

00:26:22.950 --> 00:26:24.830 align:middle line:90%
it's easy to tell.

00:26:24.830 --> 00:26:28.050 align:middle line:90%
You Americans, you're so lonely.

00:26:28.050 --> 00:26:30.580 align:middle line:84%
You even walk down
the street alone.

00:26:30.580 --> 00:26:32.790 align:middle line:90%
Anybody can see that.

00:26:32.790 --> 00:26:33.630 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: It's true.

00:26:33.630 --> 00:26:34.130 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:26:34.130 --> 00:26:37.600 align:middle line:84%
>>MCTAGGART: And that really
was a fascinating thing for me,

00:26:37.600 --> 00:26:41.580 align:middle line:84%
looking at the whole
need we have to belong.

00:26:41.580 --> 00:26:44.165 align:middle line:84%
Because scientists looking
at the opposite side, people

00:26:44.165 --> 00:26:47.430 align:middle line:84%
who commit suicide,
find that suicides

00:26:47.430 --> 00:26:50.100 align:middle line:84%
suffer from what
psychologists say--

00:26:50.100 --> 00:26:52.527 align:middle line:90%
call excessive individuation.

00:26:52.527 --> 00:26:53.110 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:26:53.110 --> 00:26:54.800 align:middle line:90%
>>MCTAGGART: They feel left out.

00:26:54.800 --> 00:26:58.280 align:middle line:84%
And being left out is the one
thing that human beings cannot

00:26:58.280 --> 00:26:58.920 align:middle line:90%
bear.

00:26:58.920 --> 00:26:59.961 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: We cannot bear.

00:26:59.961 --> 00:27:01.334 align:middle line:90%
We suffer in all ways from that.

00:27:01.334 --> 00:27:03.250 align:middle line:84%
And we're going to come
back in just a minute.

00:27:03.250 --> 00:27:04.666 align:middle line:84%
And we're going
to talk about some

00:27:04.666 --> 00:27:06.610 align:middle line:84%
of the people that
suffer the most

00:27:06.610 --> 00:27:09.520 align:middle line:84%
as a result of
extreme individuation.

00:27:09.520 --> 00:27:11.420 align:middle line:90%
We'll be right back.

