00:27:28.752 --> 00:27:29.710 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Welcome back.

00:27:29.710 --> 00:27:32.470 align:middle line:84%
Just before we broke, we
were talking about suicides,

00:27:32.470 --> 00:27:34.400 align:middle line:84%
and I was explaining
that you would probably

00:27:34.400 --> 00:27:36.810 align:middle line:84%
be surprised to find out
where some of the highest

00:27:36.810 --> 00:27:38.304 align:middle line:90%
rates of suicides were.

00:27:38.304 --> 00:27:39.720 align:middle line:84%
>>MCTAGGART: A
group of scientists

00:27:39.720 --> 00:27:44.700 align:middle line:84%
got together with people looking
at the population and differing

00:27:44.700 --> 00:27:46.056 align:middle line:90%
populations.

00:27:46.056 --> 00:27:47.430 align:middle line:84%
And they wanted
to find out where

00:27:47.430 --> 00:27:50.160 align:middle line:84%
the most suicides
occurred in America.

00:27:50.160 --> 00:27:53.940 align:middle line:84%
And they assumed it would be
in the poorest neighborhoods.

00:27:53.940 --> 00:27:54.690 align:middle line:90%
So they looked.

00:27:54.690 --> 00:27:57.610 align:middle line:84%
And they did find that the most
suicides occur in the poorest

00:27:57.610 --> 00:27:58.880 align:middle line:90%
neighborhoods.

00:27:58.880 --> 00:28:00.380 align:middle line:84%
Then they wanted
to find out where's

00:28:00.380 --> 00:28:03.230 align:middle line:90%
the next group of suicides.

00:28:03.230 --> 00:28:05.710 align:middle line:90%
And it wasn't the next poorest.

00:28:05.710 --> 00:28:08.820 align:middle line:84%
It was actually in the
richest neighborhoods.

00:28:08.820 --> 00:28:11.950 align:middle line:84%
Richest neighborhoods in America
had the second highest rate

00:28:11.950 --> 00:28:13.260 align:middle line:90%
of suicide.

00:28:13.260 --> 00:28:15.070 align:middle line:84%
And what they found
when they started

00:28:15.070 --> 00:28:18.400 align:middle line:84%
looking why was that
it was the people who

00:28:18.400 --> 00:28:21.880 align:middle line:84%
made just a little bit less
than everybody else around them.

00:28:21.880 --> 00:28:25.070 align:middle line:84%
And that, again to
these scientists,

00:28:25.070 --> 00:28:29.190 align:middle line:84%
was another indication of
this lack of belonging,

00:28:29.190 --> 00:28:31.605 align:middle line:84%
people feeling like
financial outcasts.

00:28:31.605 --> 00:28:32.547 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:28:32.547 --> 00:28:34.880 align:middle line:84%
>>MCTAGGART: And that becomes
something they can't bear.

00:28:34.880 --> 00:28:37.463 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Well, and when you're
in that kind of social strata,

00:28:37.463 --> 00:28:41.430 align:middle line:84%
there's so much fear surrounding
not being able to keep up

00:28:41.430 --> 00:28:44.529 align:middle line:84%
or being perceived as
slightly less than.

00:28:44.529 --> 00:28:46.070 align:middle line:84%
I mean, it creates
tremendous amounts

00:28:46.070 --> 00:28:47.210 align:middle line:90%
of fear in these individuals.

00:28:47.210 --> 00:28:48.793 align:middle line:84%
And of course, a lot
of these suicides

00:28:48.793 --> 00:28:51.150 align:middle line:84%
are the ones that make
it to the evening news.

00:28:51.150 --> 00:28:52.150 align:middle line:90%
>>MCTAGGART: Absolutely.

00:28:52.150 --> 00:28:54.566 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And so it's not as
though we're not aware of it.

00:28:54.566 --> 00:28:56.340 align:middle line:84%
But as they say, it's
lonely at the top.

00:28:56.340 --> 00:28:59.980 align:middle line:84%
Well, I mean if you call that
the top, it's lonely indeed.

00:28:59.980 --> 00:29:02.250 align:middle line:84%
And I thought you made
a lovely case for that.

00:29:02.250 --> 00:29:04.760 align:middle line:84%
And there was another area
having to do with wealth.

00:29:04.760 --> 00:29:08.330 align:middle line:84%
And actually they're using MRIs
in brain activity, brain wave

00:29:08.330 --> 00:29:11.640 align:middle line:90%
activity, about fairness issues.

00:29:11.640 --> 00:29:15.150 align:middle line:84%
And we're going to get into
several examples of games

00:29:15.150 --> 00:29:18.620 align:middle line:84%
and such, and studies, and
experiments around this.

00:29:18.620 --> 00:29:20.460 align:middle line:84%
But one of the things
that intrigued me

00:29:20.460 --> 00:29:23.830 align:middle line:84%
was how the MRI
operated when you

00:29:23.830 --> 00:29:27.470 align:middle line:84%
had a wealthy, well off
individual, when they were

00:29:27.470 --> 00:29:30.970 align:middle line:84%
able to give some of what
they have to someone they

00:29:30.970 --> 00:29:33.000 align:middle line:84%
love, to their partner
or so, and what

00:29:33.000 --> 00:29:35.210 align:middle line:84%
happened to their
brain activity.

00:29:35.210 --> 00:29:37.620 align:middle line:84%
And what happened
when someone that

00:29:37.620 --> 00:29:40.590 align:middle line:84%
was on the lowest part of
the socioeconomic scale

00:29:40.590 --> 00:29:44.130 align:middle line:84%
was given what they felt
they were worth and due.

00:29:44.130 --> 00:29:46.540 align:middle line:84%
Very similar brain
activity, and this

00:29:46.540 --> 00:29:48.050 align:middle line:84%
had to do-- this
was interesting,

00:29:48.050 --> 00:29:50.360 align:middle line:84%
because it had to
do with what's fair

00:29:50.360 --> 00:29:53.300 align:middle line:84%
and our perceptions on a very
deep level of what's fair.

00:29:53.300 --> 00:29:55.264 align:middle line:84%
We're not living
in a fair culture.

00:29:55.264 --> 00:29:55.930 align:middle line:90%
>>MCTAGGART: No.

00:29:55.930 --> 00:29:59.614 align:middle line:84%
And scientists, as you say,
have discovered two things

00:29:59.614 --> 00:30:00.530 align:middle line:90%
that you talked about.

00:30:00.530 --> 00:30:05.980 align:middle line:84%
One is the idea of giving
feels as good to us

00:30:05.980 --> 00:30:07.480 align:middle line:90%
as eating or having sex.

00:30:07.480 --> 00:30:09.810 align:middle line:84%
You know, we're told
we're born to be selfish.

00:30:09.810 --> 00:30:11.520 align:middle line:84%
We're told even our
genes are selfish.

00:30:11.520 --> 00:30:13.250 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Well, listen to
Richard Dawkins, right.

00:30:13.250 --> 00:30:14.250 align:middle line:90%
>>MCTAGGART: Absolutely.

00:30:14.250 --> 00:30:17.210 align:middle line:84%
We believe that we're
supposed to act selfishly

00:30:17.210 --> 00:30:19.390 align:middle line:84%
because we've been
programmed to do so.

00:30:19.390 --> 00:30:24.810 align:middle line:84%
Well, first of all,
the science shows not.

00:30:24.810 --> 00:30:26.650 align:middle line:84%
The science shows
that we feel as

00:30:26.650 --> 00:30:30.420 align:middle line:84%
good about giving as
eating and having sex.

00:30:30.420 --> 00:30:33.590 align:middle line:84%
And secondly, there's also
another thing in our brains

00:30:33.590 --> 00:30:36.600 align:middle line:84%
that's an it's not fair
button that goes off

00:30:36.600 --> 00:30:40.640 align:middle line:84%
when we're not given enough, or
even when we're given too much.

00:30:40.640 --> 00:30:42.950 align:middle line:84%
Our brains scream,
it's not fair.

00:30:42.950 --> 00:30:44.620 align:middle line:90%
So even those bankers out there.

00:30:44.620 --> 00:30:46.620 align:middle line:84%
There's something in their
brains that's saying,

00:30:46.620 --> 00:30:47.470 align:middle line:90%
it's not fair.

00:30:47.470 --> 00:30:49.600 align:middle line:90%
We're being given too much.

00:30:49.600 --> 00:30:52.490 align:middle line:84%
But as you say, there's
an equalizing mechanism.

00:30:52.490 --> 00:30:54.290 align:middle line:84%
So studies that
have shown when, you

00:30:54.290 --> 00:30:56.750 align:middle line:84%
know, where they've sort
of stacked the deck,

00:30:56.750 --> 00:30:59.140 align:middle line:84%
where somebody's getting
too much and another person

00:30:59.140 --> 00:31:01.290 align:middle line:84%
is getting too
little in the study.

00:31:01.290 --> 00:31:04.250 align:middle line:84%
Let's say it's an
employment type game.

00:31:04.250 --> 00:31:07.590 align:middle line:84%
They find that people feel
better when-- if they're

00:31:07.590 --> 00:31:10.110 align:middle line:84%
getting too much, if they
get less the next time.

00:31:10.110 --> 00:31:13.100 align:middle line:84%
And if they're not given
enough, if they're given more.

00:31:13.100 --> 00:31:16.430 align:middle line:84%
So we feel good
about equalizing.

00:31:16.430 --> 00:31:18.810 align:middle line:84%
It's there in our hard
wiring to feel good.

00:31:18.810 --> 00:31:20.900 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: It's like
we're seeking balance

00:31:20.900 --> 00:31:24.220 align:middle line:84%
on a psychospiritual,
emotional level.

00:31:24.220 --> 00:31:27.110 align:middle line:84%
And then there was an actual
game, the ultimatum game.

00:31:27.110 --> 00:31:29.040 align:middle line:84%
>>MCTAGGART: Well,
this is a wonderful way

00:31:29.040 --> 00:31:31.960 align:middle line:84%
of showing that we're
inherently fear.

00:31:31.960 --> 00:31:34.250 align:middle line:84%
The ultimatum game's the
simplest kind of game.

00:31:34.250 --> 00:31:37.300 align:middle line:84%
And John Nash was the person
who came up with game theory.

00:31:37.300 --> 00:31:40.640 align:middle line:90%
So these follow on.

00:31:40.640 --> 00:31:45.890 align:middle line:84%
It the ultimatum game, let's
say you and I have never met.

00:31:45.890 --> 00:31:47.480 align:middle line:90%
I'm given 10 bucks.

00:31:47.480 --> 00:31:51.700 align:middle line:84%
You're assigned to
me as my partner.

00:31:51.700 --> 00:31:53.400 align:middle line:84%
I'm never going
to meet you again.

00:31:53.400 --> 00:31:55.480 align:middle line:84%
And I'm told I can
take this 10 bucks,

00:31:55.480 --> 00:31:58.920 align:middle line:84%
and I can split it with
you in any way I want.

00:31:58.920 --> 00:32:03.280 align:middle line:84%
And if I split it with you, if
you decide to keep the split,

00:32:03.280 --> 00:32:05.350 align:middle line:84%
then we both get our
share of the money.

00:32:05.350 --> 00:32:08.900 align:middle line:84%
If you say no to it, neither
of us gets any money.

00:32:08.900 --> 00:32:12.010 align:middle line:84%
So the assumption is
that I will always

00:32:12.010 --> 00:32:14.920 align:middle line:90%
keep $9, or something like that.

00:32:14.920 --> 00:32:17.320 align:middle line:90%
And I'll give you about $1.

00:32:17.320 --> 00:32:19.090 align:middle line:84%
And even though it's
derisory, you'll

00:32:19.090 --> 00:32:21.820 align:middle line:84%
take it because something's
better than nothing.

00:32:21.820 --> 00:32:24.210 align:middle line:84%
Well, this game has been
played all around the world,

00:32:24.210 --> 00:32:27.090 align:middle line:84%
even with cultures that don't
have money, where they're

00:32:27.090 --> 00:32:29.540 align:middle line:90%
playing with tobacco, not money.

00:32:29.540 --> 00:32:33.457 align:middle line:84%
And the most common
split is 50%.

00:32:33.457 --> 00:32:34.040 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Mhm.

00:32:34.040 --> 00:32:36.330 align:middle line:90%
That makes total sense to me.

00:32:36.330 --> 00:32:38.980 align:middle line:84%
>>MCTAGGART: The most
common split is 50%.

00:32:38.980 --> 00:32:41.980 align:middle line:84%
But the other interesting
thing is about fairness,

00:32:41.980 --> 00:32:44.770 align:middle line:84%
is we expect people
to be fair back.

00:32:44.770 --> 00:32:46.860 align:middle line:90%
We expect reciprocity.

00:32:46.860 --> 00:32:48.860 align:middle line:84%
And scientists have
shown this with a thing

00:32:48.860 --> 00:32:50.680 align:middle line:90%
called the public goods game.

00:32:50.680 --> 00:32:54.260 align:middle line:84%
Now in this game, let's say
we've got a group of us.

00:32:54.260 --> 00:32:56.090 align:middle line:90%
We're all given 10 bucks.

00:32:56.090 --> 00:32:59.000 align:middle line:84%
We're all told to put a certain
percentage of that money

00:32:59.000 --> 00:33:00.010 align:middle line:90%
into a pot.

00:33:00.010 --> 00:33:04.370 align:middle line:84%
And it's going to be
redistributed to all of us.

00:33:04.370 --> 00:33:08.610 align:middle line:84%
So the real secret to the game
is the more everybody puts in,

00:33:08.610 --> 00:33:11.590 align:middle line:90%
the better everybody makes out.

00:33:11.590 --> 00:33:13.110 align:middle line:90%
And initially, it's true.

00:33:13.110 --> 00:33:16.600 align:middle line:84%
Everybody is generous
usually, except maybe one

00:33:16.600 --> 00:33:19.460 align:middle line:84%
or two people who
are less generous.

00:33:19.460 --> 00:33:21.887 align:middle line:84%
So this pisses the
rest of the people off.

00:33:21.887 --> 00:33:22.470 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:33:22.470 --> 00:33:25.527 align:middle line:84%
>>MCTAGGART: So in subsequent
games, they put in less.

00:33:25.527 --> 00:33:26.860 align:middle line:90%
And they put in less after that.

00:33:26.860 --> 00:33:29.642 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So we start becoming
stingier ourselves in response,

00:33:29.642 --> 00:33:31.850 align:middle line:84%
because we're feeling this
lack of fairness innately.

00:33:31.850 --> 00:33:33.058 align:middle line:90%
>>MCTAGGART: Exactly, Regina.

00:33:33.058 --> 00:33:36.310 align:middle line:84%
And so ultimately, no
one puts in anything.

00:33:36.310 --> 00:33:38.140 align:middle line:84%
And that's kind of
where we are right now.

00:33:38.140 --> 00:33:39.600 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes, I would say so.

00:33:39.600 --> 00:33:39.730 align:middle line:84%
>>MCTAGGART: We're
in a public goods

00:33:39.730 --> 00:33:41.970 align:middle line:90%
game no one wants to play.

00:33:41.970 --> 00:33:42.880 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Absolutely.

00:33:42.880 --> 00:33:44.990 align:middle line:84%
And there was another one,
a woman named Browning.

00:33:44.990 --> 00:33:47.640 align:middle line:84%
The study she did I
found interesting,

00:33:47.640 --> 00:33:49.720 align:middle line:84%
because this is a
computer generated model,

00:33:49.720 --> 00:33:51.060 align:middle line:90%
from what I understood.

00:33:51.060 --> 00:33:53.280 align:middle line:84%
>>MCTAGGART: No, this
used one of those games.

00:33:53.280 --> 00:33:55.930 align:middle line:84%
And it was trying
to figure out what

00:33:55.930 --> 00:33:59.342 align:middle line:84%
was going to be--
in this game, it

00:33:59.342 --> 00:34:01.300 align:middle line:84%
was almost like a survival
of the fittest game.

00:34:01.300 --> 00:34:04.090 align:middle line:84%
Because what happened
was they modeled it

00:34:04.090 --> 00:34:07.760 align:middle line:84%
so that the winners of any
game, of any couple of games,

00:34:07.760 --> 00:34:11.489 align:middle line:84%
would then split their
binary code and make a baby.

00:34:11.489 --> 00:34:13.870 align:middle line:84%
And I so that super
winner would then

00:34:13.870 --> 00:34:16.730 align:middle line:90%
play other codes, essentially.

00:34:16.730 --> 00:34:18.989 align:middle line:84%
And what they found,
which was so amazing--

00:34:18.989 --> 00:34:20.350 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Do you want to give
the framework for the game

00:34:20.350 --> 00:34:20.850 align:middle line:90%
itself?

00:34:20.850 --> 00:34:22.460 align:middle line:84%
Because it about
the partnership.

00:34:22.460 --> 00:34:25.199 align:middle line:84%
This particular one
was about a partnership

00:34:25.199 --> 00:34:28.460 align:middle line:84%
where you could either--
you had four options.

00:34:28.460 --> 00:34:30.658 align:middle line:84%
You can choose to go-- if
they had a man and wife,

00:34:30.658 --> 00:34:32.949 align:middle line:84%
for example, and the woman
chooses to go to the ballet.

00:34:32.949 --> 00:34:36.210 align:middle line:84%
The man chooses to go to
a bullfight, whatever.

00:34:36.210 --> 00:34:37.969 align:middle line:90%
You had a choice.

00:34:37.969 --> 00:34:39.805 align:middle line:84%
The woman could
accompany the man

00:34:39.805 --> 00:34:43.230 align:middle line:84%
to his game, what he wants to
do, whether she wants or not.

00:34:43.230 --> 00:34:45.030 align:middle line:84%
He could accompany
her to the ballet.

00:34:45.030 --> 00:34:46.482 align:middle line:90%
She could go to her own thing.

00:34:46.482 --> 00:34:48.940 align:middle line:84%
Or they could each go to the
other thing without the other,

00:34:48.940 --> 00:34:49.440 align:middle line:90%
right.

00:34:49.440 --> 00:34:51.381 align:middle line:84%
And so those are the
four variables in that.

00:34:51.381 --> 00:34:53.880 align:middle line:84%
>>MCTAGGART: And it was called
the Battle of the Sexes game.

00:34:53.880 --> 00:34:56.580 align:middle line:84%
They always have these
really funny, exotic titles.

00:34:56.580 --> 00:34:58.130 align:middle line:90%
So she modeled it.

00:34:58.130 --> 00:35:00.320 align:middle line:84%
As I say, the winners
of the different games

00:35:00.320 --> 00:35:01.930 align:middle line:90%
would then make a baby.

00:35:01.930 --> 00:35:05.760 align:middle line:84%
And then those super winners
would play each other.

00:35:05.760 --> 00:35:07.220 align:middle line:84%
And after a while,
she modeled it.

00:35:07.220 --> 00:35:09.297 align:middle line:84%
And with computer
programming, you could play--

00:35:09.297 --> 00:35:10.130 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Endlessly.

00:35:10.130 --> 00:35:12.960 align:middle line:84%
>>MCTAGGART: Thousands of
these games very quickly.

00:35:12.960 --> 00:35:16.740 align:middle line:84%
She called up her thesis tutor
and said, oh my goodness.

00:35:16.740 --> 00:35:19.420 align:middle line:90%
They seem to be taking turns.

00:35:19.420 --> 00:35:23.190 align:middle line:84%
So the computer
model itself found

00:35:23.190 --> 00:35:27.030 align:middle line:84%
that cooperation was
the best outcome,

00:35:27.030 --> 00:35:30.900 align:middle line:84%
that when you took turns, when
you were fair and reciprocated,

00:35:30.900 --> 00:35:33.000 align:middle line:90%
you actually won better.

00:35:33.000 --> 00:35:35.270 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And it makes sense,
just like the other one,

00:35:35.270 --> 00:35:39.030 align:middle line:84%
like the ultimatum
experiment where you can--

00:35:39.030 --> 00:35:40.580 align:middle line:84%
everyone ended up
essentially giving

00:35:40.580 --> 00:35:42.150 align:middle line:90%
each other half their money.

00:35:42.150 --> 00:35:43.220 align:middle line:90%
And that feels right.

00:35:43.220 --> 00:35:47.390 align:middle line:84%
I find even in simple
situations such as playing games

00:35:47.390 --> 00:35:49.780 align:middle line:84%
with friends, board
games, or card games.

00:35:49.780 --> 00:35:53.150 align:middle line:84%
It's fun to be in a bit of
competition, so to speak,

00:35:53.150 --> 00:35:54.180 align:middle line:90%
and doing your best.

00:35:54.180 --> 00:35:58.100 align:middle line:84%
But I can't stand it if it gets
lopsided and anybody is clearly

00:35:58.100 --> 00:35:58.995 align:middle line:90%
not winning.

00:35:58.995 --> 00:35:59.745 align:middle line:90%
>>MCTAGGART: Yeah.

00:35:59.745 --> 00:36:00.090 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: I don't
like the game anymore.

00:36:00.090 --> 00:36:02.040 align:middle line:84%
>>MCTAGGART: I mean,
we all have that in us.

00:36:02.040 --> 00:36:04.500 align:middle line:84%
We will have-- and
here's the reason

00:36:04.500 --> 00:36:09.330 align:middle line:84%
that it's so important, aside
from just it being the kind

00:36:09.330 --> 00:36:11.000 align:middle line:90%
and the right thing to do.

00:36:11.000 --> 00:36:13.520 align:middle line:84%
I mean, scientists
have demonstrated

00:36:13.520 --> 00:36:17.500 align:middle line:84%
that the more
unfair any society,

00:36:17.500 --> 00:36:20.440 align:middle line:84%
and they've looked at all
of the Western societies,

00:36:20.440 --> 00:36:22.010 align:middle line:84%
the more fair--
and by unfair, they

00:36:22.010 --> 00:36:26.850 align:middle line:84%
mean really a huge
disparity between income

00:36:26.850 --> 00:36:31.400 align:middle line:84%
between rich and poor and a
disparity between opportunity.

00:36:31.400 --> 00:36:35.350 align:middle line:84%
The more unfair any society,
the worse off that society

00:36:35.350 --> 00:36:38.850 align:middle line:84%
is in terms of all the
important social indicators

00:36:38.850 --> 00:36:43.960 align:middle line:84%
like education, crime,
health, mental health, all

00:36:43.960 --> 00:36:45.440 align:middle line:90%
those sorts of things.

00:36:45.440 --> 00:36:50.180 align:middle line:84%
And America, which was worked
out to be the most unfair

00:36:50.180 --> 00:36:53.020 align:middle line:84%
of all of the Western
societies, when they looked

00:36:53.020 --> 00:36:57.220 align:middle line:84%
at all those social indicators,
they found we're at the bottom.

00:36:57.220 --> 00:37:00.150 align:middle line:84%
We, the richest country in the
world, we're at the bottom.

00:37:00.150 --> 00:37:03.800 align:middle line:84%
We've got the worst
stats for education,

00:37:03.800 --> 00:37:06.780 align:middle line:84%
for health, et
cetera-- on and on.

00:37:06.780 --> 00:37:09.020 align:middle line:90%
And we're the most unfair.

00:37:09.020 --> 00:37:11.160 align:middle line:90%
So they've made that connection.

00:37:11.160 --> 00:37:13.440 align:middle line:84%
And a real interesting
one I found

00:37:13.440 --> 00:37:17.950 align:middle line:84%
was one state that had
the fewest problems in all

00:37:17.950 --> 00:37:20.160 align:middle line:84%
of the United States
was New Hampshire.

00:37:20.160 --> 00:37:23.004 align:middle line:84%
And they also found
that is the least unfair

00:37:23.004 --> 00:37:23.920 align:middle line:90%
of all of the states--

00:37:23.920 --> 00:37:24.410 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Interesting.

00:37:24.410 --> 00:37:24.910 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:37:24.910 --> 00:37:26.550 align:middle line:84%
>>MCTAGGART: In terms
of this disparity

00:37:26.550 --> 00:37:29.010 align:middle line:84%
between-- great disparity
between rich and poor

00:37:29.010 --> 00:37:30.490 align:middle line:90%
and opportunity.

00:37:30.490 --> 00:37:35.040 align:middle line:84%
So fairness creates a better
situation for everybody,

00:37:35.040 --> 00:37:36.412 align:middle line:90%
rich or poor.

00:37:36.412 --> 00:37:36.995 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:37:36.995 --> 00:37:40.171 align:middle line:84%
>>MCTAGGART: You know, there's--
the one really interesting--

00:37:40.171 --> 00:37:42.670 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And we're not talking
communism or socialism here.

00:37:42.670 --> 00:37:47.430 align:middle line:84%
We're talking about an innate,
almost cellular knowing

00:37:47.430 --> 00:37:48.480 align:middle line:90%
of fairness.

00:37:48.480 --> 00:37:49.520 align:middle line:90%
>>MCTAGGART: Absolutely.

00:37:49.520 --> 00:37:50.250 align:middle line:90%
Absolutely.

00:37:50.250 --> 00:37:53.491 align:middle line:84%
And you know, this has a really
important bearing on the rich,

00:37:53.491 --> 00:37:53.990 align:middle line:90%
too.

00:37:53.990 --> 00:37:57.300 align:middle line:84%
Because there was a study
that I've looked at that

00:37:57.300 --> 00:37:59.730 align:middle line:84%
I found really
fascinating of rich folks.

00:37:59.730 --> 00:38:01.481 align:middle line:84%
They found-- they
looked at neighborhoods.

00:38:01.481 --> 00:38:02.980 align:middle line:84%
And they wanted to
find out who were

00:38:02.980 --> 00:38:04.580 align:middle line:84%
the people who
were the most ill.

00:38:04.580 --> 00:38:06.670 align:middle line:84%
And they found
they were the rich.

00:38:06.670 --> 00:38:08.890 align:middle line:84%
The richest person on any
block is the most ill,

00:38:08.890 --> 00:38:11.450 align:middle line:84%
because they found
that person had created

00:38:11.450 --> 00:38:14.350 align:middle line:84%
a bunker mentality,
an isolated mentality.

00:38:14.350 --> 00:38:18.420 align:middle line:84%
And it was that isolation
that ultimately made him ill.

00:38:18.420 --> 00:38:21.687 align:middle line:84%
As I said earlier, that
Gary Cooper character

00:38:21.687 --> 00:38:23.970 align:middle line:84%
is the perfect candidate
for a heart attack,

00:38:23.970 --> 00:38:26.650 align:middle line:84%
because they found
this lack of belonging,

00:38:26.650 --> 00:38:30.060 align:middle line:84%
which is all about--
belonging is about connecting,

00:38:30.060 --> 00:38:33.810 align:middle line:84%
about giving, about agreeing,
about being part of,

00:38:33.810 --> 00:38:36.360 align:middle line:90%
about fairness.

00:38:36.360 --> 00:38:40.690 align:middle line:84%
You know, belonging is probably
the best drug we can take.

00:38:40.690 --> 00:38:44.970 align:middle line:84%
It not only protects us
against heart attack,

00:38:44.970 --> 00:38:47.950 align:middle line:84%
but also stroke,
even the common cold.

00:38:47.950 --> 00:38:51.660 align:middle line:84%
I mean, they found looking
at heart attack patients

00:38:51.660 --> 00:38:54.280 align:middle line:84%
that only half have
the usual risk factors.

00:38:54.280 --> 00:38:56.392 align:middle line:84%
The other half
are simply lonely.

00:38:56.392 --> 00:38:57.600 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: That's interesting.

00:38:57.600 --> 00:38:59.700 align:middle line:84%
Because in the past,
the statistics,

00:38:59.700 --> 00:39:01.200 align:middle line:84%
certainly in the
United States, were

00:39:01.200 --> 00:39:03.890 align:middle line:84%
that men had a much higher
degree of heart disease,

00:39:03.890 --> 00:39:04.700 align:middle line:90%
for example.

00:39:04.700 --> 00:39:06.632 align:middle line:84%
Now the women have
caught up with that.

00:39:06.632 --> 00:39:07.340 align:middle line:90%
>>MCTAGGART: Hmm.

00:39:07.340 --> 00:39:10.330 align:middle line:84%
Well, women are working
all hours, trying

00:39:10.330 --> 00:39:11.840 align:middle line:84%
to juggle all sorts
of things, don't

00:39:11.840 --> 00:39:13.631 align:middle line:84%
have the social networks
they used to have.

00:39:13.631 --> 00:39:15.790 align:middle line:90%
And so it's about belonging.

00:39:15.790 --> 00:39:17.150 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: It is about belonging.

00:39:17.150 --> 00:39:19.470 align:middle line:84%
Now, you talked in
the book about, again,

00:39:19.470 --> 00:39:22.740 align:middle line:84%
this essential
knowingness, the wisdom

00:39:22.740 --> 00:39:25.810 align:middle line:84%
of a group of people
for its own survival.

00:39:25.810 --> 00:39:29.040 align:middle line:84%
And in the case you
used, it was a hill tribe

00:39:29.040 --> 00:39:31.780 align:middle line:84%
around the tsunami
of 2004, which

00:39:31.780 --> 00:39:35.580 align:middle line:84%
I thought was fascinating, the
way in which the elder started

00:39:35.580 --> 00:39:39.420 align:middle line:84%
observing and noticing
the patterns of behavior.

00:39:39.420 --> 00:39:41.000 align:middle line:84%
Maybe you can share
the rest of that.

00:39:41.000 --> 00:39:43.500 align:middle line:84%
>>MCTAGGART: Well, one of the
things I wanted to look at

00:39:43.500 --> 00:39:45.940 align:middle line:90%
was how do we recover this bond.

00:39:45.940 --> 00:39:49.560 align:middle line:84%
And you know, I haven't really
defined bond in this show

00:39:49.560 --> 00:39:50.080 align:middle line:90%
so far.

00:39:50.080 --> 00:39:55.220 align:middle line:84%
But by bond, I mean connections
so integral and profound

00:39:55.220 --> 00:39:56.600 align:middle line:84%
that it's impossible
to say where

00:39:56.600 --> 00:39:58.650 align:middle line:84%
one thing ends and
another thing begins.

00:39:58.650 --> 00:40:01.050 align:middle line:84%
And that's really
what my book argues,

00:40:01.050 --> 00:40:02.540 align:middle line:90%
is that's what we are part of.

00:40:02.540 --> 00:40:05.530 align:middle line:84%
We are an intergalactic
super-organism.

00:40:05.530 --> 00:40:09.250 align:middle line:84%
And we can only understand
each other and our lives

00:40:09.250 --> 00:40:11.330 align:middle line:90%
if we live in that way.

00:40:11.330 --> 00:40:13.570 align:middle line:84%
So I asked myself,
how do we recover it?

00:40:13.570 --> 00:40:16.270 align:middle line:84%
And there were four things
I thought were important.

00:40:16.270 --> 00:40:20.510 align:middle line:84%
The first was about seeing
much more holistically.

00:40:20.510 --> 00:40:25.210 align:middle line:84%
And in the 2004 tsunami where
a quarter million people died,

00:40:25.210 --> 00:40:29.130 align:middle line:84%
four tribes watched the whole
thing from a mountaintop.

00:40:29.130 --> 00:40:32.450 align:middle line:84%
And the Westerners
were amazed by this.

00:40:32.450 --> 00:40:34.480 align:middle line:84%
If they had been
able to forecast

00:40:34.480 --> 00:40:37.390 align:middle line:84%
this what their Western,
the best Western equipment

00:40:37.390 --> 00:40:41.230 align:middle line:84%
couldn't do, and when they
actually looked at why

00:40:41.230 --> 00:40:44.830 align:middle line:84%
and they talked to these elders,
they said, how did you know?

00:40:44.830 --> 00:40:46.950 align:middle line:90%
And they said oh, simple.

00:40:46.950 --> 00:40:48.680 align:middle line:84%
The fish were
swimming a bit funny,

00:40:48.680 --> 00:40:50.750 align:middle line:84%
and the animals were
acting a little bit odd.

00:40:50.750 --> 00:40:53.180 align:middle line:84%
And you know, the wind
had changed direction.

00:40:53.180 --> 00:40:54.250 align:middle line:90%
And so we--

00:40:54.250 --> 00:40:56.280 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: The children
were behaving badly.

00:40:56.280 --> 00:40:57.030 align:middle line:90%
>>MCTAGGART: Yeah.

00:40:57.030 --> 00:40:58.740 align:middle line:84%
The children were
behaving badly.

00:40:58.740 --> 00:41:02.650 align:middle line:84%
And so we realized that
water was going to pull back

00:41:02.650 --> 00:41:04.960 align:middle line:90%
and hurl forward with fury.

00:41:04.960 --> 00:41:07.719 align:middle line:90%
And so that was amazing to them.

00:41:07.719 --> 00:41:09.510 align:middle line:84%
And when they looked
further at this tribe,

00:41:09.510 --> 00:41:11.360 align:middle line:84%
they found they've
actually learned

00:41:11.360 --> 00:41:13.320 align:middle line:84%
to see in a very,
very different way.

00:41:13.320 --> 00:41:15.570 align:middle line:84%
I mean, they can
swim in the water,

00:41:15.570 --> 00:41:20.090 align:middle line:84%
and they're able to
distinguish little brown clams

00:41:20.090 --> 00:41:23.790 align:middle line:84%
from little brown stones 15
yards away in the ocean bottom

00:41:23.790 --> 00:41:27.980 align:middle line:84%
without any kind of
swimming aids like goggles.

00:41:27.980 --> 00:41:30.130 align:middle line:84%
They've taught
themselves, their eyes,

00:41:30.130 --> 00:41:32.420 align:middle line:84%
to be almost like
a camera aperture.

00:41:32.420 --> 00:41:36.570 align:middle line:84%
And they've been able to see so
much more holistically, so much

00:41:36.570 --> 00:41:39.400 align:middle line:84%
more detail, than
we in the West can.

00:41:39.400 --> 00:41:43.040 align:middle line:84%
And that really has to do
with how we're trained to see.

00:41:43.040 --> 00:41:47.310 align:middle line:84%
We are trained to
be so individual.

00:41:47.310 --> 00:41:49.150 align:middle line:84%
We're trained, if
you're as old as I am,

00:41:49.150 --> 00:41:51.740 align:middle line:84%
you remember books like
"Fun With Dick and Jane."

00:41:51.740 --> 00:41:51.870 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Oh, yeah.

00:41:51.870 --> 00:41:52.410 align:middle line:90%
I remember that.

00:41:52.410 --> 00:41:53.590 align:middle line:90%
>>MCTAGGART: And you know.

00:41:53.590 --> 00:41:55.290 align:middle line:84%
And we were taught
to see the comings

00:41:55.290 --> 00:41:57.220 align:middle line:90%
and goings of individuals.

00:41:57.220 --> 00:42:02.290 align:middle line:84%
And so ultimately, we focus on
the individual things so much

00:42:02.290 --> 00:42:05.940 align:middle line:84%
that we cannot see these subtle
connections that tie things

00:42:05.940 --> 00:42:06.550 align:middle line:90%
together.

00:42:06.550 --> 00:42:08.760 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And this seems
to be one differentiating

00:42:08.760 --> 00:42:12.210 align:middle line:84%
factor socially between
many of the eastern cultures

00:42:12.210 --> 00:42:15.290 align:middle line:84%
and the west, is this sense
of belonging and family.

00:42:15.290 --> 00:42:17.120 align:middle line:90%
But even that is changing.

00:42:17.120 --> 00:42:20.230 align:middle line:84%
In fact, in Thailand, I
was there a few years ago,

00:42:20.230 --> 00:42:23.650 align:middle line:84%
and we were with some
students, American students.

00:42:23.650 --> 00:42:26.470 align:middle line:84%
And they were doing
some work in the field

00:42:26.470 --> 00:42:28.600 align:middle line:90%
of science and sociology.

00:42:28.600 --> 00:42:30.100 align:middle line:84%
And they were talking
about the fact

00:42:30.100 --> 00:42:34.165 align:middle line:84%
that there was a huge
upswing in the prescription

00:42:34.165 --> 00:42:37.820 align:middle line:84%
of antidepressant drugs
to the elder generation.

00:42:37.820 --> 00:42:40.960 align:middle line:84%
The reason being, they
now have Starbucks,

00:42:40.960 --> 00:42:43.620 align:middle line:90%
or their Wawee coffee.

00:42:43.620 --> 00:42:45.650 align:middle line:84%
And you saw the young
people in their 30s.

00:42:45.650 --> 00:42:46.900 align:middle line:90%
They had Western clothing on.

00:42:46.900 --> 00:42:49.940 align:middle line:84%
They had their Mac books
there at the coffee shops.

00:42:49.940 --> 00:42:52.260 align:middle line:84%
And the children were
leaving the hill.

00:42:52.260 --> 00:42:54.920 align:middle line:84%
They were leaving the cities
to go find their own way,

00:42:54.920 --> 00:42:56.700 align:middle line:90%
as we have done for so long.

00:42:56.700 --> 00:42:59.620 align:middle line:84%
And the family does not know how
to survive without each other

00:42:59.620 --> 00:43:02.720 align:middle line:84%
there and were rapidly falling
into a state of depression

00:43:02.720 --> 00:43:05.460 align:middle line:84%
among the elderly,
which is very, very sad.

00:43:05.460 --> 00:43:09.370 align:middle line:84%
And again, they already had
that part of the picture,

00:43:09.370 --> 00:43:10.492 align:middle line:90%
it sounds like, right.

00:43:10.492 --> 00:43:11.200 align:middle line:90%
>>MCTAGGART: Yes.

00:43:11.200 --> 00:43:13.440 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: But how do
you stop any kind of,

00:43:13.440 --> 00:43:15.110 align:middle line:84%
if you want to call
it progress, change

00:43:15.110 --> 00:43:17.570 align:middle line:84%
once a younger
generation has decided

00:43:17.570 --> 00:43:19.050 align:middle line:90%
it's in their best interest.

00:43:19.050 --> 00:43:20.800 align:middle line:84%
>>MCTAGGART: By showing
them that maybe it

00:43:20.800 --> 00:43:22.860 align:middle line:90%
isn't the progress.

00:43:22.860 --> 00:43:26.430 align:middle line:84%
I think, you know, there's
some wonderful happy mediums.

00:43:26.430 --> 00:43:29.710 align:middle line:84%
The whole idea that we have
is such an either or mentality

00:43:29.710 --> 00:43:30.700 align:middle line:90%
here in the West.

00:43:30.700 --> 00:43:34.960 align:middle line:84%
We think it has to be communism
or socialism, or capitalism.

00:43:34.960 --> 00:43:38.950 align:middle line:84%
We don't see that there are
all kinds of shades of gray,

00:43:38.950 --> 00:43:39.570 align:middle line:90%
you know.

00:43:39.570 --> 00:43:42.500 align:middle line:84%
There all kinds of
ways to differentiate.

00:43:42.500 --> 00:43:43.720 align:middle line:90%
We can have progress.

00:43:43.720 --> 00:43:48.690 align:middle line:90%
We can have Western mod cons.

00:43:48.690 --> 00:43:50.390 align:middle line:90%
But we can also have community.

00:43:50.390 --> 00:43:52.220 align:middle line:90%
And that's really my message.

00:43:52.220 --> 00:43:55.000 align:middle line:84%
The message of "The
Bond" is the only way

00:43:55.000 --> 00:43:59.090 align:middle line:84%
we are going to evolve as
a society, as a species,

00:43:59.090 --> 00:44:02.110 align:middle line:84%
is to understand
that we are here--

00:44:02.110 --> 00:44:05.030 align:middle line:84%
we are interconnected,
so interconnected,

00:44:05.030 --> 00:44:07.470 align:middle line:84%
and that we have to
live in that way.

00:44:07.470 --> 00:44:11.410 align:middle line:84%
We have to recreate the
kinds of close knit community

00:44:11.410 --> 00:44:15.520 align:middle line:84%
that we are programmed
to thrive in.

00:44:15.520 --> 00:44:19.550 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: At the same time, not
fall into only associating with

00:44:19.550 --> 00:44:20.700 align:middle line:90%
like.

00:44:20.700 --> 00:44:22.900 align:middle line:84%
Because that's the
conundrum there.

00:44:22.900 --> 00:44:24.242 align:middle line:90%
We need each other.

00:44:24.242 --> 00:44:24.950 align:middle line:90%
>>MCTAGGART: Yes.

00:44:24.950 --> 00:44:26.920 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Yet at
the same time, we

00:44:26.920 --> 00:44:29.970 align:middle line:84%
cloister ourselves among
people only of like mind

00:44:29.970 --> 00:44:32.940 align:middle line:84%
and are very intolerant
to outside perceptions

00:44:32.940 --> 00:44:38.010 align:middle line:84%
within this attempt to
make ourselves feel safe.

00:44:38.010 --> 00:44:39.010 align:middle line:90%
>>MCTAGGART: Absolutely.

00:44:39.010 --> 00:44:42.450 align:middle line:84%
And that was the
next piece of how

00:44:42.450 --> 00:44:44.830 align:middle line:84%
to recover the bond I
wanted to talk about

00:44:44.830 --> 00:44:47.940 align:middle line:84%
was this whole idea of
learning to relate to people

00:44:47.940 --> 00:44:50.460 align:middle line:84%
in a different way, in a
much more holistic way.

00:44:50.460 --> 00:44:55.030 align:middle line:84%
That was the second thing I felt
was really important to wipe

00:44:55.030 --> 00:44:59.240 align:middle line:84%
out in that hard drive we have
to change in ourselves in order

00:44:59.240 --> 00:45:06.690 align:middle line:84%
to evolve is we're taught and
we now look much more for us

00:45:06.690 --> 00:45:10.010 align:middle line:90%
and revile them.

00:45:10.010 --> 00:45:12.090 align:middle line:84%
And us is becoming
smaller and smaller.

00:45:12.090 --> 00:45:13.767 align:middle line:84%
And them is becoming
bigger and bigger.

00:45:13.767 --> 00:45:14.350 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:45:14.350 --> 00:45:16.190 align:middle line:84%
>>MCTAGGART: And
as you say, we look

00:45:16.190 --> 00:45:18.990 align:middle line:84%
to connect with people
who are only like us.

00:45:18.990 --> 00:45:22.030 align:middle line:84%
And that is kind of almost
a personal justification.

00:45:22.030 --> 00:45:26.140 align:middle line:84%
We want our friends to be
another I, another person.

00:45:26.140 --> 00:45:27.641 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: A reflection
of ourselves.

00:45:27.641 --> 00:45:28.515 align:middle line:90%
>>MCTAGGART: Exactly.

00:45:28.515 --> 00:45:30.470 align:middle line:84%
And we don't know how
to connect with people

00:45:30.470 --> 00:45:32.090 align:middle line:90%
who are not like us anymore.

00:45:32.090 --> 00:45:34.300 align:middle line:84%
And we certainly
see it in America.

00:45:34.300 --> 00:45:38.590 align:middle line:84%
We're polarizing so much
again on political grounds,

00:45:38.590 --> 00:45:41.470 align:middle line:84%
on economic grounds, on
every kind of ground.

00:45:41.470 --> 00:45:46.180 align:middle line:84%
We are really dividing
and not understanding

00:45:46.180 --> 00:45:50.400 align:middle line:84%
about bringing ourselves
together and making

00:45:50.400 --> 00:45:53.370 align:middle line:84%
the relationship the
most important thing.

00:45:53.370 --> 00:45:57.220 align:middle line:84%
And I found a really interesting
example of that in a guy

00:45:57.220 --> 00:46:01.637 align:middle line:84%
called Orland Bishop, who's
working in Watts in California.

00:46:01.637 --> 00:46:02.220 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:46:02.220 --> 00:46:03.060 align:middle line:90%
That was beautiful.

00:46:03.060 --> 00:46:04.476 align:middle line:84%
>>MCTAGGART: You
know, and here he

00:46:04.476 --> 00:46:07.450 align:middle line:84%
is working with gang
members, rival gang members,

00:46:07.450 --> 00:46:09.920 align:middle line:84%
teaching the members of
the Crips and the Bloods,

00:46:09.920 --> 00:46:12.330 align:middle line:84%
the most notorious
gangs in America,

00:46:12.330 --> 00:46:14.600 align:middle line:84%
how you relate to each
other in wholeness.

00:46:14.600 --> 00:46:16.370 align:middle line:90%
Talk about a fool's errand.

00:46:16.370 --> 00:46:17.960 align:middle line:90%
But he's succeeding.

00:46:17.960 --> 00:46:19.750 align:middle line:84%
Because he's
teaching them methods

00:46:19.750 --> 00:46:22.330 align:middle line:84%
of getting past
those differences

00:46:22.330 --> 00:46:24.770 align:middle line:84%
to connect on a
deeper soul level

00:46:24.770 --> 00:46:28.040 align:middle line:84%
by sharing deeply about
themselves and finding that,

00:46:28.040 --> 00:46:30.270 align:middle line:84%
even though they have
differences of beliefs,

00:46:30.270 --> 00:46:31.510 align:middle line:90%
they have common values.

00:46:31.510 --> 00:46:33.810 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And he asked them
really probing questions

00:46:33.810 --> 00:46:36.160 align:middle line:84%
to get them to open up
in front of each other,

00:46:36.160 --> 00:46:38.070 align:middle line:90%
I mean deeply personal.

00:46:38.070 --> 00:46:41.040 align:middle line:84%
I think it was
something like what

00:46:41.040 --> 00:46:43.200 align:middle line:84%
was the event that
essentially helped

00:46:43.200 --> 00:46:46.250 align:middle line:84%
you come to the conclusion
your life was not going

00:46:46.250 --> 00:46:47.860 align:middle line:84%
to be what you had
hoped it would be.

00:46:47.860 --> 00:46:48.734 align:middle line:90%
>>MCTAGGART: Exactly.

00:46:48.734 --> 00:46:51.830 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: These interrupting,
often traumatic events.

00:46:51.830 --> 00:46:54.280 align:middle line:84%
This really brought
out some, well,

00:46:54.280 --> 00:46:56.600 align:middle line:84%
vulnerability and
humility in these kids.

00:46:56.600 --> 00:46:57.730 align:middle line:90%
>>MCTAGGART: Exactly.

00:46:57.730 --> 00:47:01.600 align:middle line:84%
And that became the glue
that connected people.

00:47:01.600 --> 00:47:05.000 align:middle line:84%
But that kind of deep sharing
from the heart is so powerful.

00:47:05.000 --> 00:47:08.090 align:middle line:84%
I mean, it's brought
together people

00:47:08.090 --> 00:47:11.317 align:middle line:84%
who are very polarized, like
pro-life, pro-choice people.

00:47:11.317 --> 00:47:11.900 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:47:11.900 --> 00:47:12.400 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:47:12.400 --> 00:47:15.070 align:middle line:84%
And also the story
of the old Germans

00:47:15.070 --> 00:47:17.777 align:middle line:84%
that went back and revisited
their history in Belarus.

00:47:17.777 --> 00:47:18.860 align:middle line:90%
That was an amazing story.

00:47:18.860 --> 00:47:21.020 align:middle line:84%
>>MCTAGGART: This
was an amazing story.

00:47:21.020 --> 00:47:25.670 align:middle line:84%
A batch of Germans
went back to Belarus

00:47:25.670 --> 00:47:31.790 align:middle line:84%
to help with some of the
rebuilding after Chernobyl.

00:47:31.790 --> 00:47:34.570 align:middle line:84%
And this had been-- these were
people who had been in the war.

00:47:34.570 --> 00:47:37.000 align:middle line:84%
So of course, they had been
on the side of the Nazis.

00:47:37.000 --> 00:47:41.210 align:middle line:84%
And they had created a
lot of destruction there.

00:47:41.210 --> 00:47:43.000 align:middle line:84%
So they wanted to
try to make amends.

00:47:43.000 --> 00:47:44.000 align:middle line:90%
So they were doing that.

00:47:44.000 --> 00:47:45.666 align:middle line:84%
And they were with
their host one night.

00:47:45.666 --> 00:47:49.380 align:middle line:84%
And one of the old Germans
stood up and he said,

00:47:49.380 --> 00:47:51.020 align:middle line:90%
he wanted to toast his host.

00:47:51.020 --> 00:47:54.960 align:middle line:84%
And he said, I wanted to say
this must never happen again.

00:47:54.960 --> 00:47:56.270 align:middle line:90%
And he started talking.

00:47:56.270 --> 00:47:58.037 align:middle line:90%
And he just began to sob.

00:47:58.037 --> 00:48:00.120 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And he had spent
time in a Russian camp.

00:48:00.120 --> 00:48:01.578 align:middle line:84%
>>MCTAGGART: He
had been in a camp.

00:48:01.578 --> 00:48:03.490 align:middle line:84%
And he had felt
sorry for himself.

00:48:03.490 --> 00:48:06.510 align:middle line:84%
But he started just
thinking of the destruction

00:48:06.510 --> 00:48:09.650 align:middle line:84%
his country had wreaked
on this country.

00:48:09.650 --> 00:48:10.800 align:middle line:90%
And he began to sob.

00:48:10.800 --> 00:48:16.280 align:middle line:84%
And at that point, an old
woman, an old Belarusian woman,

00:48:16.280 --> 00:48:18.500 align:middle line:84%
came over and hugged
him and kissed him.

00:48:18.500 --> 00:48:22.350 align:middle line:84%
It's like that
expression of real sorrow

00:48:22.350 --> 00:48:25.920 align:middle line:84%
and real repentance
and an opening up

00:48:25.920 --> 00:48:28.870 align:middle line:84%
of really speaking
from the heart

00:48:28.870 --> 00:48:33.790 align:middle line:84%
crosses and creates a
situation of forgiveness

00:48:33.790 --> 00:48:34.985 align:middle line:90%
that nothing else can.

00:48:34.985 --> 00:48:35.860 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Absolutely.

00:48:35.860 --> 00:48:38.750 align:middle line:84%
And the thing is, when you're
in a competitive society like

00:48:38.750 --> 00:48:42.290 align:middle line:84%
the societies of the West,
you don't-- you feel you have

00:48:42.290 --> 00:48:44.890 align:middle line:84%
to protect your
turf at all costs,

00:48:44.890 --> 00:48:47.700 align:middle line:84%
especially your
internal emotional turf.

00:48:47.700 --> 00:48:51.460 align:middle line:84%
And so people, at all
costs, avoid that kind

00:48:51.460 --> 00:48:54.840 align:middle line:84%
of really intimate
disclosure and weakness

00:48:54.840 --> 00:48:56.070 align:middle line:90%
in front of others.

00:48:56.070 --> 00:48:57.481 align:middle line:90%
We have to let that go.

00:48:57.481 --> 00:48:58.480 align:middle line:90%
>>MCTAGGART: Absolutely.

00:48:58.480 --> 00:49:01.360 align:middle line:84%
And when we do,
when we understand

00:49:01.360 --> 00:49:04.590 align:middle line:84%
you don't have to agree,
but when you share,

00:49:04.590 --> 00:49:06.020 align:middle line:90%
you make that connection.

00:49:06.020 --> 00:49:08.010 align:middle line:84%
I mean, there was a
wonderful situation

00:49:08.010 --> 00:49:10.230 align:middle line:84%
of pro-life and
pro-choice women.

00:49:10.230 --> 00:49:13.390 align:middle line:84%
After some shootings
in Planned Parenthood,

00:49:13.390 --> 00:49:14.950 align:middle line:84%
the leaders of
both sides decided

00:49:14.950 --> 00:49:16.810 align:middle line:90%
they had to come together.

00:49:16.810 --> 00:49:18.580 align:middle line:84%
And they began
meeting in secret.

00:49:18.580 --> 00:49:20.370 align:middle line:84%
And they learned
how to share deeply

00:49:20.370 --> 00:49:24.930 align:middle line:84%
to stop demonizing the other
and to value the connection.

00:49:24.930 --> 00:49:27.940 align:middle line:84%
And at the end of a few years,
they held a press conference.

00:49:27.940 --> 00:49:32.020 align:middle line:84%
And the press, of course, said
to them, so who won the debate?

00:49:32.020 --> 00:49:33.750 align:middle line:90%
And they said well, no one.

00:49:33.750 --> 00:49:37.110 align:middle line:84%
In the act of sharing so
deeply, we-- both sides

00:49:37.110 --> 00:49:41.350 align:middle line:84%
felt more firmly in
what they believe.

00:49:41.350 --> 00:49:43.310 align:middle line:84%
And so they said oh,
it was a failure then.

00:49:43.310 --> 00:49:44.430 align:middle line:90%
They said, no, no.

00:49:44.430 --> 00:49:47.210 align:middle line:84%
Because when there've been
threats on Planned Parenthood,

00:49:47.210 --> 00:49:49.830 align:middle line:84%
it's been the
pro-life people who

00:49:49.830 --> 00:49:51.490 align:middle line:90%
warned the pro-choice people.

00:49:51.490 --> 00:49:53.890 align:middle line:84%
But now, of course,
we go out together.

00:49:53.890 --> 00:49:54.970 align:middle line:90%
We party together.

00:49:54.970 --> 00:49:56.310 align:middle line:90%
We love each other.

00:49:56.310 --> 00:49:59.040 align:middle line:84%
We look after each
other's children.

00:49:59.040 --> 00:50:00.430 align:middle line:90%
We love each other.

00:50:00.430 --> 00:50:03.180 align:middle line:84%
And it's that, that
power of deep sharing,

00:50:03.180 --> 00:50:05.959 align:middle line:84%
that becomes the bridge
across the fence.

00:50:05.959 --> 00:50:08.000 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So now with the
time we have remaining,

00:50:08.000 --> 00:50:10.830 align:middle line:84%
we need to start looking at the
how to, the mechanics of it,

00:50:10.830 --> 00:50:11.537 align:middle line:90%
the solutions.

00:50:11.537 --> 00:50:13.370 align:middle line:84%
Because the last part
of your book is really

00:50:13.370 --> 00:50:14.520 align:middle line:90%
dedicated to this.

00:50:14.520 --> 00:50:16.270 align:middle line:84%
And I want to take
your lead on this.

00:50:16.270 --> 00:50:18.050 align:middle line:84%
Because there's a
lot to go through

00:50:18.050 --> 00:50:19.280 align:middle line:90%
in a short amount of time.

00:50:19.280 --> 00:50:22.400 align:middle line:84%
But how do we
begin, first of all,

00:50:22.400 --> 00:50:28.030 align:middle line:84%
creating this larger vision
of wholeness and this dialogue

00:50:28.030 --> 00:50:30.940 align:middle line:84%
that brings us into this deep
compassion for one another,

00:50:30.940 --> 00:50:34.514 align:middle line:84%
so we can even begin to reform
the society on this level.

00:50:34.514 --> 00:50:35.180 align:middle line:90%
>>MCTAGGART: OK.

00:50:35.180 --> 00:50:39.260 align:middle line:84%
Well, there are four things
that we need to do, I feel.

00:50:39.260 --> 00:50:41.810 align:middle line:84%
All of us, even the
most spiritual of us,

00:50:41.810 --> 00:50:44.420 align:middle line:84%
have this hard drive
that's been programmed

00:50:44.420 --> 00:50:46.670 align:middle line:84%
with I win, you
lose individualism,

00:50:46.670 --> 00:50:48.810 align:middle line:90%
individualistic competitiveness.

00:50:48.810 --> 00:50:50.700 align:middle line:90%
That has to be wiped clean.

00:50:50.700 --> 00:50:52.690 align:middle line:84%
The first thing has
to be this whole idea

00:50:52.690 --> 00:50:54.950 align:middle line:84%
of seeing much
more holistically.

00:50:54.950 --> 00:50:57.710 align:middle line:84%
And in the book, I
talk a lot about-- I

00:50:57.710 --> 00:51:02.310 align:middle line:84%
provide a whole bunch of
exercises to show people

00:51:02.310 --> 00:51:05.470 align:middle line:84%
how to learn to
see on many levels,

00:51:05.470 --> 00:51:10.120 align:middle line:84%
seeing with the gut
hunch, seeing the unseen,

00:51:10.120 --> 00:51:13.730 align:middle line:84%
seeing watching
people on many levels,

00:51:13.730 --> 00:51:17.640 align:middle line:84%
seeing without
judgment, understanding.

00:51:17.640 --> 00:51:21.140 align:middle line:84%
As I write in the
book about Don Beck,

00:51:21.140 --> 00:51:24.240 align:middle line:84%
who invented spiral dynamics,
and who has been very much

00:51:24.240 --> 00:51:26.130 align:middle line:90%
involved as a peace keeper.

00:51:26.130 --> 00:51:31.460 align:middle line:84%
He helped both the black
people and the white people

00:51:31.460 --> 00:51:34.080 align:middle line:84%
before the end of
apartheid in South Africa

00:51:34.080 --> 00:51:36.740 align:middle line:84%
by showing the white
people, for instance,

00:51:36.740 --> 00:51:39.370 align:middle line:84%
that the tribes
were not all alike,

00:51:39.370 --> 00:51:42.360 align:middle line:84%
that there were lots of
different shades of gray,

00:51:42.360 --> 00:51:45.100 align:middle line:84%
that there were lots of
different shades of belief.

00:51:45.100 --> 00:51:48.080 align:middle line:84%
And that-- being
able to see that

00:51:48.080 --> 00:51:50.850 align:middle line:84%
and to see with much more
detail about other people,

00:51:50.850 --> 00:51:54.710 align:middle line:84%
and to distinguish different
belief systems, is important.

00:51:54.710 --> 00:51:59.640 align:middle line:84%
So there are many things, as I
say, I have on just exercises,

00:51:59.640 --> 00:52:02.310 align:middle line:84%
learning to see the
whole that are important.

00:52:02.310 --> 00:52:06.840 align:middle line:84%
Learning to relate very
differently, that's number two.

00:52:06.840 --> 00:52:11.080 align:middle line:84%
We talked a little bit about
sharing deeply, understanding

00:52:11.080 --> 00:52:14.560 align:middle line:84%
and valuing, because
we've lost this a lot.

00:52:14.560 --> 00:52:19.890 align:middle line:84%
The whole idea of changing
what a relationship is for.

00:52:19.890 --> 00:52:22.820 align:middle line:84%
A relationship is
about the connection.

00:52:22.820 --> 00:52:24.350 align:middle line:90%
It's not about agreeing.

00:52:24.350 --> 00:52:26.750 align:middle line:84%
It's not about finding
another I in that person.

00:52:26.750 --> 00:52:28.370 align:middle line:90%
It's about connection.

00:52:28.370 --> 00:52:31.560 align:middle line:84%
And I have a lot of exercises
in the book about how

00:52:31.560 --> 00:52:34.160 align:middle line:84%
to connect with people
who are not like you,

00:52:34.160 --> 00:52:38.510 align:middle line:84%
how to value that connection
above anything else,

00:52:38.510 --> 00:52:42.230 align:middle line:84%
and how to learn to find
the connection, even

00:52:42.230 --> 00:52:45.900 align:middle line:84%
among all of this other belief
stuff that's so different.

00:52:45.900 --> 00:52:51.000 align:middle line:84%
If you're a Republican, you
can find common values even

00:52:51.000 --> 00:52:54.130 align:middle line:90%
in somebody who's a Democrat.

00:52:54.130 --> 00:52:56.580 align:middle line:84%
If somebody's a rabid
Republican and somebody's

00:52:56.580 --> 00:53:00.100 align:middle line:84%
a rabid Democrat,
I guarantee you,

00:53:00.100 --> 00:53:03.330 align:middle line:84%
you still have mostly
the same beliefs.

00:53:03.330 --> 00:53:05.570 align:middle line:90%
You have mostly the same values.

00:53:05.570 --> 00:53:09.460 align:middle line:84%
You still love
God, in most cases.

00:53:09.460 --> 00:53:12.070 align:middle line:84%
You still love your
family and children.

00:53:12.070 --> 00:53:17.370 align:middle line:84%
You still want to fix the roads
and fix the infrastructure.

00:53:17.370 --> 00:53:19.820 align:middle line:84%
And you still want to
balance the budget.

00:53:19.820 --> 00:53:22.550 align:middle line:90%
We have lots of similar things.

00:53:22.550 --> 00:53:27.030 align:middle line:84%
And it's training yourself
to find those common values

00:53:27.030 --> 00:53:30.700 align:middle line:84%
underneath the different
beliefs and systems.

00:53:30.700 --> 00:53:33.050 align:middle line:90%
So getting past that.

00:53:33.050 --> 00:53:37.310 align:middle line:84%
The third thing I talk
about is really important,

00:53:37.310 --> 00:53:40.390 align:middle line:84%
the whole idea of the
superordinate goal.

00:53:40.390 --> 00:53:43.990 align:middle line:84%
And by that, that's a big word
for meaning coming together

00:53:43.990 --> 00:53:45.190 align:middle line:90%
for a common goal.

00:53:45.190 --> 00:53:46.570 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:53:46.570 --> 00:53:48.510 align:middle line:84%
>>MCTAGGART: It was
illustrated so perfectly

00:53:48.510 --> 00:53:52.230 align:middle line:84%
in a study called the Robber's
Cave Experiment, where

00:53:52.230 --> 00:53:54.660 align:middle line:84%
scientists took a bunch
of 12-year-old boys,

00:53:54.660 --> 00:53:58.250 align:middle line:84%
put them in two buses,
sent them to summer camp,

00:53:58.250 --> 00:54:03.530 align:middle line:84%
and had them create identities
for themselves, separate places

00:54:03.530 --> 00:54:06.630 align:middle line:84%
to sleep, and engaged them
in highly competitive games.

00:54:06.630 --> 00:54:08.590 align:middle line:84%
And the camp
counselors in this case

00:54:08.590 --> 00:54:10.850 align:middle line:84%
were all psychologists
in disguise.

00:54:10.850 --> 00:54:13.370 align:middle line:84%
And the kids, after a while,
were killing each other.

00:54:13.370 --> 00:54:15.487 align:middle line:84%
They were ripping up
each other's flags.

00:54:15.487 --> 00:54:16.820 align:middle line:90%
They were beating each other up.

00:54:16.820 --> 00:54:18.020 align:middle line:90%
They hated each other.

00:54:18.020 --> 00:54:20.640 align:middle line:84%
So then the counselors
got them together

00:54:20.640 --> 00:54:22.500 align:middle line:84%
to work together for
some common goals.

00:54:22.500 --> 00:54:24.690 align:middle line:84%
They created a series
of crises in the camp.

00:54:24.690 --> 00:54:26.510 align:middle line:84%
Put an impediment
in the water supply.

00:54:26.510 --> 00:54:29.640 align:middle line:84%
Boys had to work together
to get rid of it.

00:54:29.640 --> 00:54:32.510 align:middle line:84%
Truck in the ditch, had to work
together to get rid of th--

00:54:32.510 --> 00:54:33.940 align:middle line:90%
bring it out of the ditch.

00:54:33.940 --> 00:54:36.170 align:middle line:84%
And lo and behold,
miracles happened.

00:54:36.170 --> 00:54:39.050 align:middle line:84%
The boys began to eat
together, chat together,

00:54:39.050 --> 00:54:40.110 align:middle line:90%
befriend each other.

00:54:40.110 --> 00:54:44.660 align:middle line:84%
And by the end of this
session, this summer camp,

00:54:44.660 --> 00:54:49.000 align:middle line:84%
they unanimously voted to
ride home on the bus together.

00:54:49.000 --> 00:54:53.750 align:middle line:84%
What he really talked about, the
psychologist and the scientist

00:54:53.750 --> 00:54:56.340 align:middle line:84%
who did the study,
invented this whole idea

00:54:56.340 --> 00:54:58.950 align:middle line:84%
of superordinate
goal, coming together

00:54:58.950 --> 00:55:01.230 align:middle line:84%
for a common goal,
barn building.

00:55:01.230 --> 00:55:02.030 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:55:02.030 --> 00:55:06.390 align:middle line:84%
>>MCTAGGART: That is such a
powerful thing in a community,

00:55:06.390 --> 00:55:08.870 align:middle line:84%
coming together to work
together for a common goal.

00:55:08.870 --> 00:55:12.330 align:middle line:84%
Because when people work
together for a common goal,

00:55:12.330 --> 00:55:15.220 align:middle line:84%
their brain waves start
working in synchrony.

00:55:15.220 --> 00:55:17.830 align:middle line:90%
We start resonating as one.

00:55:17.830 --> 00:55:21.280 align:middle line:84%
And that's something I'm working
on a lot in little groups,

00:55:21.280 --> 00:55:25.720 align:middle line:84%
intention groups, watching how
when people intend together,

00:55:25.720 --> 00:55:26.890 align:middle line:90%
a group of eight or 12.

00:55:26.890 --> 00:55:28.740 align:middle line:90%
I call it the power of eight.

00:55:28.740 --> 00:55:31.460 align:middle line:84%
They begin resonating
in synchrony.

00:55:31.460 --> 00:55:34.920 align:middle line:84%
Not only does the person seem
to get better that they're

00:55:34.920 --> 00:55:38.070 align:middle line:84%
sending intention to, but all
of the people in the group

00:55:38.070 --> 00:55:40.020 align:middle line:90%
become a virtuous circle.

00:55:40.020 --> 00:55:44.050 align:middle line:84%
They also find they
are feeling better.

00:55:44.050 --> 00:55:45.130 align:middle line:90%
They feel more connected.

00:55:45.130 --> 00:55:48.800 align:middle line:84%
And in many cases, they are
also healed in some way.

00:55:48.800 --> 00:55:51.170 align:middle line:84%
And they're permanently
changed, because they

00:55:51.170 --> 00:55:55.317 align:middle line:84%
feel this connection, this
palpable sense of oneness.

00:55:55.317 --> 00:55:56.150 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: And it is.

00:55:56.150 --> 00:55:59.330 align:middle line:84%
It's all about, as you say,
it's the connection itself.

00:55:59.330 --> 00:56:03.560 align:middle line:84%
And there was a wonderful
metaphor about music being more

00:56:03.560 --> 00:56:05.160 align:middle line:84%
about the space
between the notes.

00:56:05.160 --> 00:56:06.690 align:middle line:90%
And it's the same with us.

00:56:06.690 --> 00:56:09.450 align:middle line:84%
It's that connectivity
between the individuals

00:56:09.450 --> 00:56:10.670 align:middle line:90%
that makes life worth living.

00:56:10.670 --> 00:56:12.640 align:middle line:84%
And we only have a
few seconds left.

00:56:12.640 --> 00:56:14.960 align:middle line:84%
If you have any one
final comment to make,

00:56:14.960 --> 00:56:16.800 align:middle line:90%
I'd love to hear it.

00:56:16.800 --> 00:56:19.290 align:middle line:84%
>>MCTAGGART: Really
important to understand, now

00:56:19.290 --> 00:56:21.300 align:middle line:84%
that we're so frightened
about what's going on,

00:56:21.300 --> 00:56:23.450 align:middle line:84%
is that you can be
the change agent.

00:56:23.450 --> 00:56:27.210 align:middle line:84%
In "The Bond," I
talk a lot about how

00:56:27.210 --> 00:56:31.640 align:middle line:84%
tiny actions, even leaving
your change in a Coke machine,

00:56:31.640 --> 00:56:36.280 align:middle line:84%
which one woman did, changed the
whole culture of her business.

00:56:36.280 --> 00:56:40.060 align:middle line:84%
It reminded her
company of generosity.

00:56:40.060 --> 00:56:42.460 align:middle line:84%
And when generosity
is the currency,

00:56:42.460 --> 00:56:43.914 align:middle line:90%
the game starts changing.

00:56:43.914 --> 00:56:45.080 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Absolutely, Lynne.

00:56:45.080 --> 00:56:46.750 align:middle line:84%
Thank you so much
for being with us.

00:56:46.750 --> 00:56:49.340 align:middle line:84%
And I have to say, she's
made a beautiful case

00:56:49.340 --> 00:56:50.930 align:middle line:90%
for choosing cooperation.

00:56:50.930 --> 00:56:52.850 align:middle line:84%
I highly recommend
reading "The Bond."

00:56:52.850 --> 00:56:54.840 align:middle line:84%
As I said before,
it's a must read,

00:56:54.840 --> 00:56:57.684 align:middle line:84%
even forming a group of
eight around it if you can.

00:56:57.684 --> 00:56:59.600 align:middle line:84%
Meanwhile, you might
also enjoy our interviews

00:56:59.600 --> 00:57:01.224 align:middle line:84%
with Howard Martin
and Bruce Lipton who

00:57:01.224 --> 00:57:03.610 align:middle line:84%
also touch on these
subjects very closely.

00:57:03.610 --> 00:57:05.860 align:middle line:84%
Until tell next time, thank
you for joining us here

00:57:05.860 --> 00:57:07.890 align:middle line:90%
on Gaiam TV.

